<HEADLINE> Permanent Dwellings To Be Built in Turkish Quake Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ANKARA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Permanent dwellings will be
constructed early next year to house earthquake victims in place of
 makeshift shelters, reported the Anatolia News Agency on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
State Minister Hasan Gemici broke the news when he was visiting
 quake survivors in Seforihisar County of western Izmir Province.
</P>
<P>
The houses will be built in February or March next year.
</P>
<P>
Gemici said that the geophysical and geological works regarding
 the permanent dwellings had been finished and all the planned
dwellings will be completed within 2000.  The Social Aid and
Solidarity Fund has appropriated 100 million Turkish lira (500,000
liras are equal to one U.S. dollar) rent aid to those whose houses
collapsed during the quake disasters.
</P>
<P>
A total of 107,000 families are reportedly receiving the quake
aid and the government has granted 20 trillion liras for the quake
survivors.
</P>
<P>
On August 17, a 7.4-magnitude tremor devastated Istanbul in
western Turkey, killing more than 15,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Before the wounds were healed, a 7.2-magnitude quake battered
Bolu province in northwestern Turkey on November 12. Several
hundred people died in the disaster.
</P>
<P>
In its effort to provide urgent shelters for the quake
survivors before the driving winter set in, the government has
provided temporary accommodation in public complexes for 22victims
who would not mind leaving their hometowns for a few months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, prefabricated houses and winter-resistant tents have
</P>
<P>
been erected for those who insist on staying in the quake area.
</P>
</TEXT>
