<HEADLINE> Gore Releases Medical Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The three-page medical summary, based on a May 7 examination of
the vice president performed at the National Naval Medical Center
in Maryland, noted the Democratic presidential candidate also have
elevated cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
The vice president's medical report was released to news
organizations five days after his rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination, Bill Bradley, was forced to disclose a
non-life-threatening irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
Bradley sought hospital treatment for the condition, called
atrial fibrillation, but his heart resumed normal rhythm without
treatment.
</P>
<P>
Gore's total cholesterol is 231, a little bit higher than the
normal 200 level or below.
</P>
<P>
"It is a skin cancer of (a) sort, but it's not the bad one
everybody thinks of, which is melanoma," said Richard Tubb, the
military physician who has treated Gore since 1995. "You scrape
them off, cut them or burn them and they go away."  
</P>
</TEXT>
