<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Year-End Roundup)Mercosur Leads Economic Integration in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, December 15 (Xinhua)-- Globalization has been a
tendency in world economic development today. Latin American
countries are actively preparing themselves for their own
integration into regional, hemispheric spheres, in a movement
headed by the Common Southern Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Founded by the Asuncion Treaty of 1991, more that 94 percent
trade between Mercosur members, made up by Brazil, Argentina,
Uruguay and Paraguay, is carried through free from tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped that until year 2006, an External Common Tariff(TEC)
will be set for the total tariff universe. TEC was adopted January
1, 1995.
</P>
<P>
In December 1994, the four member countries signed the Ouro
Prieto Protocol, which recognizes the juridical personality of the
block's international rights, and attributed to Mercosur
competency to negotiate accords with third countries and
international organisms.
</P>
<P>
The success of Mercosur integration and its characteristic as
an entity provided with juridical personality has guaranteed its
relevant condition on the international scene and fundamental role
and leader in external investments in the region.
</P>
<P>
In Mercosur agenda, the first step is the creating of a widened
economic space in South America, by the concluding of an agreement
of tariff preferences and of a Free Trade Accord in year 2000
between the group and the Andean Community of Nations (CAN).
</P>
<P>
Mercosur-CAN alliance will cover 300 million people, with a GDP
close to one trillion dollars, or 13 percent of the world's total,
and will make a strategic step toward the Free Trade Area of the
Americas (FTAA) expected for year 2005.
</P>
<P>
South America's integration, besides allowing to negotiate in
block with developed countries like United States and Canada, will
foment the structural reforms of South American countries assuring
competitively in industry, condition for free trade with United
States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
The next stage will be the making up process of FTAA, project
directed to the eliminating of barriers for trade and investments
in the Hemisphere, begun December 1994 at the First Americas
Summit in Miami. (to be continued)

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
