<HEADLINE> Angolan President, U.S. Official Discuss Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Jose Eduardo
dos Santos Wednesday discussed the actual political-military
situation in Angola and in the southern African region with Thomas
Pickering, visiting U. S. Under Secretary of State for Political
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Pickering arrived here early Wednesday for a 24-hour visit with
an aim to make preparations for U.S. future policy on the issue of
Angola.
</P>
<P>
During the discussion, the Angolan president has made an
analysis on the situation in Angola and southern Africa, said
Pickering.
</P>
<P>
Before his meeting with dos Santos, the U.S. official held
talks with Angolan Foreign Minister Joao Miranda, making an
evaluation on the on-going Angolan civil conflict.
</P>
<P>
According to local analysts, Pickering's visit is very
important and crucial for the Angolan government which is hoping
to restore peace and stability around the country.
</P>
<P>
They said that Pickering will later give advice to his
government on the U.S. future Angola policy which will be made
according to the actual situation.
</P>
<P>
Since the Angolan government has in the battlefields gained
advantage on the rebels of the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), the U.S. government recently
changed its attitude to Luanda, saying that it will support the
Angolan government for the annihilation of the rebels led by Jonas
Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. had reportedly decided not to give Angola the
assistance and funds for clearing mines through governmental
channels after reading a report recently issued by the British
organization Global Witness.
</P>
<P>
During his brief visit to the southern African country,
Pickering will also meet with the Angolan Defense Minister Kundi
Paihama and leaders of the opposition Renovated Commission of the
UNITA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
