<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Settlement Policy May Blow Up Peace Efforts:                 EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
CAIRO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on
Wednesday warned that Israel's settlement activities may blow up
its peace talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa, EU Mideast envoy Miguel Moratinos said Israeli
 settlement expansion in the occupied territories could destroy the
 confidence between the Palestinians and Israel, which he said is
essential for the progress of their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Talks between the Palestinians and Israel are under way on a
permanent peace deal by next September.
</P>
<P>
Both the EU and Egypt called on Israel to stop settlement
activities in the West Bank and Gaza Strip for the realization of
peace, Moratinos was quoted as saying by Egypt's Middle East News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office in July, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
has approved more housing projects than his hardline predecessor,
Benjamin Netanyahu, in an average year.
</P>
<P>
Barak's move has angered and frustrated the Palestinians, who
have urged the international community to press the Jewish state
into freezing the settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos arrived in Cairo earlier in the day. His talks with
Moussa also dealt with the Syrian-Israeli talks, which resumed
Wednesday in Washington after a 45-month freeze.
</P>
<P>
The talks will mainly discuss Israeli withdrawal from Syria's
Golan Heights, security arrangements, right to water resources and
normalization of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"The EU intends to facilitate and support the Syrian-Israeli
negotiations," the EU envoy said.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos stressed that EU's support would not be confined to
economic aid, but could be "an effective political partnership in
some domains, with the consent of the parties involved, in order to
 reach positive results," he added.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, which wants to play a key role in mediating
 the Arab-Israeli feud, often coordinate its stance with Egypt, the
 first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with Israel and an
active mediator in the Middle East peace process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
