<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Ministers Focus on Defense Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the 19
members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) agreed
that development of an effective European Security and Defense
Identity(ESDI) will strengthen the transatlantic alliance.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are committed to reinforcing the NATO's European
pillar, they said in a final communique of their two-day meeting
being held here at NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers also reaffirmed that they support the "
development within NATO of separable but not separate capabilities
which could response to European requirements and contribute to
Alliance security".
</P>
<P>
They believe these developments "will also result in a stronger
and more balanced transatlantic relationship". The communique said
NATO has initiated discussions to address means to ensure the
development of effective mutual consultation, cooperation, and
transparency, building on the mechanisms existing between NATO and
the Western European Union, an long inert European organization
for defense policy coordinating.
</P>
<P>
The debates within NATO also include participation of non-
European Union (EU)'s European allies, as well as practical
arrangements for assured EU access to NATO planning capabilities
and for ready EU access to NATO collective assets and capabilities
on a case-by-case basis and by consensus.
</P>
<P>
"We note the European Union's decision to set a common European
headline goal and to develop collective capability goal to improve
European military capabilities," they said.
</P>
<P>
"We see these EU decisions as important steps to achieve the
goals envisaged by our heads of state and government at the
Washington Summit," they added.
</P>
<P>
During the ministerial meeting, U.S. Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott said American officials in the past have discussed
ESDI in terms of "the three D's": no decoupling of Europe's
security from that of its North American Allies; no duplication of
effort or capabilities; and no discrimination against those Allies
who are not EU members.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General George Robertson at the meeting also
reiterated a concept of "three I"s: indivisibility of the
transatlantic link, improvement of capabilities and inclusiveness
of all Allies.
</P>
<P>
"The concept binding them together should borrow the motto of
those famous heroes of French romantic literature: One for all and
all for one," Talbott told the NATO foreign ministers' year-end
conference that started Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
