<HEADLINE> Pakistan Govt to Tax Agricultural Incomes: Musharraf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his televised address to the nation Wednesday night,
Musharraf said that as part of the tax reform program, the
provincial governments will design appropriate mechanism to be
introduced in June next year.
</P>
<P>
Musharraf said in his long-awaited economic revival package
that General Sales Tax (GST) will be applied at all stages and
hoped that all citizens will work together to ensure its
implementation.
</P>
<P>
He also said that a tax ombudsman will be appointed to look
into the complaints against tax authority while revenue benches
will be established in the high courts and the supreme court to
deal with tax disputes in consultation with respective chief
justices.
</P>
<P>
Musharraf said the tax reform program is based on the principle
of lowering the tax rates and broadening the tax base as well as
simplification of procedure.
</P>
<P>
He announced a tax amnesty scheme under which tax evaders will
be able to benefit by paying 10 percent of undisclosed assets upto
March 31 next year.
</P>
<P>
On the accountability process, Musharraf said it is on course
and the delays are due to inherent shortcomings of investigative
structure supporting the newly-established National Accountability
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
He identified these shortcomings as shortage of specialists to
investigate white-collar crimes and of qualified prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive described the recovery of defaulted loans
as "a great success," saying in 45 days about 10 billion rupees (
193 million U.S. dollars) have been recovered. 
</P>
