<HEADLINE> Pakistan Govt to Focus on Agriculture, Energy, IT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The military-led government
in Pakistan Wednesday vowed to revive the economy by focusing on
the developments in sectors of Agriculture, small and medium scale
industry, oil and gas and information technology (IT).
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive General Pervaiz Musharraf said in his much-
awaited statement on the economic reform plan that those are the
four key areas that his government will focus on in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
In his televised address on Wednesday night, Musharraf said
several initiatives will be taken to unleash "the vast agriculture
potential of the country."
</P>
<P>
According to him, credit for agriculture will be augmented,
agriculture prices will be related to market mechanism, export of
milk and meat products will be encouraged and fisheries will be
promoted in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Chief Executive announced to allot permanently
large tracts of evacuee agriculture land in Tharparkar to
cultivators and state land will be allotted to landless. A special
credit package will be made to small farmers to help develop their
land.
</P>
<P>
Musharraf assured that "highest priority" will be given to
small and medium sized enterprises, saying the government will
facilitate more credit and advisory support for them.
</P>
<P>
On the energy sector where the country is spending 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars every year on imports, Musharraf said the process of
exploration and development of the known gas fields will be
accelerated and increase of foreign investment in this sector will
be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
The petroleum sector will be deregulated and margins of oil
producing companies will be rationalized, he said. The price of
liquefied petroleum gas will be deregulated and use of natural gas
encouraged.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the need for development of information technology
and software, Musharraf announced the setting up of a special
department under Ministry of Science and Technology to stimulate
growth in IT sector.
</P>
<P>
A large pool of IT professionals will be developed, charter for
IT based industries will be liberally granted, the use of Internet
will be expanded and tariff for data transfer will be reduced, he
said.
</P>
<P>
After assuming the power in a bloodless coup on October 12,
Musharraf has vowed to revitalize the weak economy of the South
Asian country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
