<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Signs Mine Sale Pact with Anglo-American </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambia signed an agreement on
the sale of two mines with Anglo-American Consortium here
Wednesday, marking a giant step forward in the privatization of
its ailing mining sector.
</P>
<P>
The assets of Nchanga Division, Konkola Division and Nampundwe
Mine have been sold for a consideration comprising 30 million U.S.
dollars cash at close, 60 million dollars future cash payments, up
to 125 million dollars in future metal price participation.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Zambia Copper Investment, an associate
company of Anglo-American Consortium, is committed to investing
over 731 million dollars, of which 208 million dollars will be
expended on the existing operations over a period of three years
and 523 million dollars will be for the construction and
development of the Konkola Deep Mining Project.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) will retain a 20
percent interest in the new company, while Zambia Copper
Investment will own 65 percent and its partners will together own
15 percent of the share holding of the mines.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Finance Minister Katele Kalumba said that the signing
of the mine sale agreement confirms the Zambian government's total
commitment to the privatization of the ZCCM and the liberalization
of the country's economy in general.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is convinced that the country's economy
needs to be restructured and liberalized to provide for efficient
flow of capital and other resources.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the signing of the agreement also
signals a possibility of a speedy and successful privatization of
the remaining mines, which should stimulate new investments and
privatizations in the other sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
ZCCM Chairman L. Shimukowa described it as "the most important
milestone" in the privatization of the mining industry of country.
</P>
<P>
The assets involved in this sale represent some of the most
important mining operations and in terms of production it accounts
for more than 70 percent of the current ZCCM output, he said.
</P>
<P>
Copper mining earns Zambia, one of the biggest copper-producing
 countries in the world. Its earnings account for about 80 percent
of the country's total export value, and its peak annual
production hit 700,000 tons in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
However, due to copper price falls in the international market
and outdated equipment, lack of new investment and mismanagement,
Zambia's annual copper output has decreased gradually to about
300,000 tons in recent years.
</P>
<P>
To revive the mining sector, the government started to sell
ZCCM assets a few years ago to attract foreign investment and
advanced technology and management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
