<HEADLINE> Lebanese Renowned Singer Acquitted of Blasphemy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 15 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese court Wednesday
acquitted the country's renowned singer Marcel Khalife of charges
on defaming Islam by putting a Koranic verse into a song.
</P>
<P>
Judge Ghada Abou Karroum told the courtroom that the singer
didn't commit any crime and so he was cleared of all charges in a
trial seen as a test case for freedom of expression in Lebanon
which is believed the most liberal in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"The singer sang seriously the Koranic verses and didn't attempt
 to insult the sanctity of Koran," the judge added.
</P>
<P>
Khalife, 49, one of the Arab world's most popular singers, was
accused of insulting Islam in October by including Koranic verses
in his song "Oh Father, It is I, Youssef."
</P>
<P>
The song based on a poem written by a renowned Palestinian poet
 Mahmoud Darwish in 1992 accounts the plight of Palestinians in
some Arab states.
</P>
<P>
The case was first filed in 1996 by Grand Mufti Mohammed Rashid
Qabbani, Lebanon's highest Sunni community leader, but was dropped
a short time later by the then-Prime Minister Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
The trial of the singer has triggered a wave of denunciations by
 intellectuals around the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Outside the Palace of Justice in downtown Beirut, hundreds of
Lebanese expressed their support to the leftist composer by
chanting pro-Khalife slogans.
</P>
<P>
After the trial, Khalife told reporters that he was satisfied
with the verdict and thanked all his supporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Remains Leading Cause of Death in Zambia: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaria remains a leading cause
of ill health and death in Zambia, Minister of Health David Mpamba
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that 12 percent to 20 percent of deaths are
due to malaria, Mpamba said at the Partners Consultative and
Sensitization Meeting on Roll Back Malaria.
</P>
<P>
Malaria cases account for 24 percent of all health center
admissions and 12 percent of hospital admissions in the southern
African country, the minister said, adding that this situation is
pathetic and cannot be allowed to continue.
</P>
<P>
"We need to identify and employ new and innovative, curative
and preventive measures that can effectively reduce the malaria
burden," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaria has become a serious menace to economic and social
development throughout the world, Mpamba pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He asked Zambia Central Board of Health to ensure that a
malaria policy is developed to guide the implementation of the
global Roll Back Malaria initiative.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was launched by the World Health Organization in
May, 1998, offering a great opportunity for joint action to tackle
the threat of malaria for human development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
