<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece's GDP to Grow at 3.8 Percent in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Greece's gross domestic product
(GDP) is expected to grow at 3.8 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters about Greece's convergence program
submitted to the European Commission Wednesday, Greek Economy and
Finance Minister Yiannos Papantoniou said that the country's GDP
growth, at 3.5 percent this year, will stand at 3.8 percent in
2000, in 2001 4.1 percent and 4.3 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The deficit will fall from the current 1.2 percent of GDP to 0.
2 percent in 2001, leading to a surplus of 0.2 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The general government debt will drop to 100.3 percent of GDP
in 2000, 99.5 percent in 2001 and 98 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Inflation, which now stands at 2.6 percent, will fall to 2.1
percent in 2000 and stabilize there for the next year before
falling marginally to 2.0 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Investment will continue to be at high levels as a percentage
of GDP. Greece's investment is already 25 percent of GDP, one of
the highest percentages in the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Employment is expected to grow, with a consequent fall in
unemployment, which currently stands at 10.5 percent and is to
fall to 8.7 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Papantoniou said that a decision on the drachma's central
parity as well as the final decision on whether Greece will be
eligible to enter the EMU is expected by June 2000 at the latest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Meets With Russian Mideast Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin
Hussein met Wednesday with visiting Russian Presidential Envoy for
Middle East Affairs Vasily Sredin on the latest developments in the
 Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the king welcomed the resumption of Syrian-
Israeli talks, which he said marked a breakthrough that would open
the door for a just settlement to enable Syria and Lebanon to
restore their lands occupied by the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Syrian-Israeli peace talks resumed Wednesday in Washington after
 a 45-month freeze and Lebanon, where Syria has been a power
broker, has also said it is willing to restart peace talks with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Sredin, who is also Russia's deputy foreign minister, conveyed
to Abdullah a letter from Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
bilateral ties and the Middle East peace process, Jordan's official
 news agency Petra reported without disclosing further details of
the letter.
</P>
<P>
The envoy briefed the king on his talks with Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad and Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa, and stressed
that Russia would exert utmost efforts to follow up and support the
 peace process between Israel and the Palestinians, Syria and
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed appreciation for King Abdullah's efforts to
help usher in a just, durable and comprehensive peace in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the two Arab countries, besides Egypt, that
have signed a peace treaty with Israel. For years, the kingdom has
been playing a key role in the peace process by trying to bridge
the differences between Israel and its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting the king, Sredin told reporters that Russia
wanted to be in the center of Arab-Israeli peace negotiations as a
sponsor and an active partner in the peace process, particularly on
 the Israeli-Syrian track.
</P>
<P>
Russia inherited a strategic partnership with Syria from the
former Soviet Union, and Sredin's visit to the region, particularly
 to Syria, was seen as an effort by Moscow to keep alive its role
and influence in the Middle East, despite its ailing economy at
home.
</P>
<P>
Sredin arrived in Amman from Syria on Monday for a three-day
visit. He is expected to leave here for Palestinian self-rule areas
 Wednesday evening.  
</P>
</TEXT>
