<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls Syrian-Israeli Talks "Big Step" Toward Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 ( Xinhua ) -- President Bill Clinton
opened historic Syrian-Israeli peace talks on Wednesday at the
White House with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara at his side.
</P>
<P>
The three gathered in the White House Rose Garden for the
showcase opening the highest-level talks Israel and Syrian have
held in a half-century, marking a resumption of negotiations
broken off nearly four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Clinton opened the two-day talks by saying that this is a "big
step" along the path toward peace.
</P>
<P>
"What we are witnessing today is not yet peace, and getting
there will require bold thinking and hard choices. But today is a
big step along that path ... for the first time in history there
is a chance for comprehensive peace between Israel and Syria," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Israel was determined "to do whatever it takes" to
put an end to 50 years of conflict and "bring about the dream of
children and mothers" in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Shara told the gathering that the Middle East was approaching a
"moment of truth" and peace with Syria meant the return of "all
its occupied land," a move that would end "the psychological fear
Israelis have been living in." 
</P>
</TEXT>
