<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Lends 1.1 Billion Dollars to Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced on
Wednesday that it has approved two loans worth 1,111 million U.S.
dollars to help Mexico sustain macroeconomic stability and
restructure banking system.
</P>
<P>
An adjustment loan of 606 million dollars will be used to
support the federal government's decentralization of health and
education services, among others, to the country's state and
municipal governments.
</P>
<P>
The decentralization adjustment loan is part of a "financial
armor" package announced by the Mexican government last June,
which includes a 4.2-billion-dollar agreement with the
International Monetary Fund, as well as financing from other
international institutions.
</P>
<P>
The loan provides financing to keep the federal fiscal balance
stable, as the country undertakes an ambitious reform of financial
arrangements between the federal government and state and
municipal governments.
</P>
<P>
These reforms include market-based rules on borrowing and debt
management by sub-national governments, hard budget constraints on
federal transfers to states and municipalities, improved
administration of public finances, and better coordination between
different levels of government.
</P>
<P>
The other loan, amounting to 505 million dollars, will help
restructure and recapitalize Mexico's banking system, in order to
stimulate job creation through renewed bank lending to small and
medium-sized entrepreneurs and businesses.
</P>
<P>
The Bank Restructuring Facility Loan provides funds to Mexico's
new bank-deposit insurance agency, Instituto de Proteccion al
Ahorro Bancario, to finance part of its debt servicing needs in
2000, arising from its mandate to restructure, sell or liquidate
five banks.
</P>
<P>
The loan also supports reforms undertaken by the Commission
National Bancaria y de Valores to improve the quantity and quality
of Mexican private banks' capital, as well as to strengthen
regulatory, accounting and disclosure standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Starts Trial of 101 PKK Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- An Ankara criminal court on
Wednesday began to try 101 members of the outlawed Kurdistan
Workers' Party (PKK), including its imprisoned leader Abdullah
Ocalan who was sentenced to death by Ankara State Security Court.
</P>
<P>
The suspects were brought to trial for being charged with
terrorist crimes they committed in Turkish southeastern province of
 Sanliurfa and its surroundings before September 12, 1980.
</P>
<P>
The hearing started in Ocalan's absence as he is being
imprisoned on Imrali island, according to a report of the Anatolia
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The suspects who faced trial include Ocalan's wife Kesire Ocalan
 and top members of PKK such as Cemil Bayik, Murat karayilan and
Mehmet Milli.
</P>
<P>
They were accused of "being members of an armed gang,
participating in murder and separatist crimes", the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
