<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF Ratifies Michael Johnson's 400 World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The world athletics governing
body IAAF ratified Michael Johnson's 400-meter world record in
Monte Carlo, Monaco on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ratification came over three months after the American
sprinter beat the 11-year-old mark of 43.29 seconds, which was
held by country fellow Butch Reynolds, by timing 43.18 on August
26 at the World Championships in Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
International Amateur Athletic Federation spokesman Giorgio
Reineri said Johnson's record was ratified on September 6 but, due
to a paperwork mixup, had never been announced.
</P>
<P>
Two other world records were also ratified: Kenyan Noah Ngeny's
1,000-meter mark (2:11.96, set in Rieti, Italy, on September 5),
and Moroccan Hicham El Guerrouj's 2,000-meter record (4:44.79, set
September 7 in Berlin). 
</P>
</TEXT>
