<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Govt. Concerned Over High Road Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- South African Transport
Minister Dullah Omar Wednesday expressed concern about the number
of road deaths so far this month, warning that the tragedy would
continue if drivers did not change their attitudes.
</P>
<P>
Launching a driving security awareness campaign here, Omar said
that more than 240 people have died in 170 road accidents since
December 1.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged all drivers to obey the traffic rules,
stressing that all nine provinces in South Africa would see an
increase in traffic law enforcement from this week, which is aimed
at drastically reducing road accidents.
</P>
<P>
The drivers appeared appreciative of the minister's efforts,
saying the campaign would help alert road users to the need of
obeying the rules.
</P>
<P>
According to South Africa's Arrive Alive Unit, 241 people have
died since December 1. Among the victims, 97 were passengers, 79
drivers and 65 pedestrians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
