<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technological Change Dominates Investment in 2000's, Says American Express </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua) - The two most dominant investment
themes of the next decade are likely to be technological change
and globalisation, according to the latest issue of Economics for
Investment published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The authors of the publication identify ten themes which have
impacted investments in the 1990's and then look forward to how
they will develop in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch of the publication, John Calverley said
some themes, like low inflation, European integration and the
focus on shareholder value are likely to continue in the same
direction.
</P>
<P>
Others, like a recovery in Japan and an under-performing US
stock market represent a form of "mean reversion", a swing back
towards the average, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Calverley, Chief Economist of American Express
Bank, free market reforms are expected to slow in most countries,
because the easy ones have been implemented.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless emerging markets as an asset class are expected to
perform much better in relative terms in the 2000's though helped
partly by lower long run returns in the US and Europe, Calverley
forecast.
</P>
<P>
Economics for Investment is the economics and financial
publication of American Express Bank, published in London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
