<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Rises in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
November's advance followed a 0.8 percent gain in October,
stronger than previously estimated, the Fed said.
</P>
<P>
Gains in output were fairly broad-based except for utilities
where, as many analysts anticipated, output fell. Unusually warm
weather in November depressed demand.
</P>
<P>
Last month, operating capacity held steady at 81 percent, the
same as in October. Generally, an operating capacity of 84 percent
would alarm economists, indicating that factories just can't
produce fast enough -- which could lead to price increases.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve will meet next week to decide whether to
boost interest rates. Many economists believe the central bank
will leave rates unchanged, citing concerns about problems that
may arise from the Y2K computer changeover.
</P>
<P>
However, the Fed is likely to bump up rates again in February
or March because the economy is still growing at a rapid pace that
could spark inflation down the road, economists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
