<HEADLINE> U.S. Trying to Put Positive Gloss over Syrian-Israel Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the gathering at the White House Rose Garden, President
Clinon launched the peace talks, calling it a "big step" along the
path of peace.
</P>
<P>
He spoke with measured optimism of a millennium-ending
comprehensive settlement between Israel and all its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara told the gathering that
peace means the return of the strategic Golan Heights, captured by
Israel during the 1967 six-day war.
</P>
<P>
He accused Israel of trying to rally sympathy for the 17,000
Jews who may be uprooted if the Golan Heights is returned to Syria.
</P>
<P>
He said more than half a million Syrian people were uprooted
from Golan villages where their forefathers lived for thousands of
years. Their homes "were totally wiped out from existence" after
Israel seized the Syrian territory.
</P>
<P>
He insisted only the return of the heights can the Israelis
live without psychological fear.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, Clinton met with both leaders of the two
countries -- Shara and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak --
separately. But the face-to-face talks between the two sides were
delayed.
</P>
<P>
At the State Department, spokesman James Foley said he could
not predict how the talks "are going to play out, and when they
will reach their endpoint."
</P>
<P>
"Let me make clear that we do not expect agreement on the
Israeli-Syrian track to emerge from the two days of meetings that
are envisaged and scheduled for this week," he said. 
</P>
