<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Mercosur Leads Economic Integration in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The FTAA, by reducing and eliminating barriers, will strengthen
the Organization of Americas (OAS) and the free circulation of
goods, services and capital between frontiers.
</P>
<P>
Facing different standards of development and dissimilar sizes
of Latin American economies and developed ones, particularly
compared with the United States, Mercosur insists on progressive
and balanced negotiations for the FTAA.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur affirms that in this way a possible loss of markets
for national products of Latin American countries facing U.S.
competition will be averted.
</P>
<P>
For Mercosur, the FTAA only means one of the existing ways for
the international insertion of Latin American economies in the
contemporary context. Parallel to the process of the hemisphere's
integration, the bloc has negotiated with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The Europeans are also interested in establishing new fronts
for dispute with the United States in the field of international
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Mutual interest and economic objectives on the medium and long
term brought closer both trade blocs on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
At the First EU-Latin America Summit held last June in Rio de
Janeiro, Mercosur and the EU analyzed the creation of a trans-
Atlantic free trade area by the year 2005, the same year the FTAA
will be put in motion.
</P>
<P>
The trans-Atlantic free trade area looks for the expansion of
its associates' economies, the strengthening of its technological
and scientific development, as well as the generating of
conditions of quality employment.
</P>
<P>
It's foreseeable that Mercosur, the EU and the Latin America-
European Union Free Trade Area will contribute to the
establishment of a fairer and more balanced relationship between
Latin America, the United States and the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani to Run for Majlis as Independent Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Former Iranian President Akbar
Hashemi Rafsanjani said here Wednesday that he would run for the
6th Majlis (parliament)as an independent candidate.
</P>
<P>
If elected, he said after registering his name for the
elections, he would try to help in reconstruction efforts, creating
 jobs, eliminating poverty and consolidating political development
to ensure stability, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, current chairman of the powerful advisory State
Expediency Council, said he supports the country's reconstruction
through the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
The former president said he was in fact willing to see handling
 of elections and major issues of the country without his presence,
 but he decided after a series of discussions and debates to
participate in the elections slated for next February.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he would accept the post of Majlis speaker,
Rafsanjani said it would depend on whether the winning candidates
would accept him.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here said that because of his reputation and
power, Rafsanjani would win the support from both the conservative
and moderate factions to be the future Majlis speaker.
</P>
<P>
They believed that Rafsanjani's presence would encourage
moderates and reformists to strive to win the sensitive
parliamentary polling, which would create a new balance of power in
 the conservative-dominated Majlis.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1934 in Iran's central Kerman Province, Rafsanjani was a
 prominent political activist before the 1979 Islamic revolution,
Majlis speaker from 1980 to 1989, and president from July 1989 to
August 1997.
</P>
<P>
He announced to run for the parliament last week after Abdollah
Nouri, the reformist hopeful for the future Majlis speaker, was
sentenced to five years imprisonment by the conservative-controlled
 Special Cleric Court.
</P>
<P>
However, reports said that Nouri, former interior minister and
vice president for development and social affairs, has also
registered to run for the Majlis and the reformist-controlled
Interior Ministry said he is qualified as a candidacy since the
appeals court has not issued verdict on him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
