<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Accepting Egypt's Conditions for Rapprochement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Kuwaiti daily al-Watan reported on Tuesday that Khatami
accepted the conditions in a message sent to his Egyptian
counterpart Hosni Mubarrak through the Egyptian information
minister who attended the Conference of Islamic Information
Ministers held in Tehran earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that Khatami called on the two countries to put
aside all their differences in order to resume their relations and
announced Tehran's readiness to take the step.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iranian official, who declined to be named, told
the Islamic Republic News Agency that the report by the Kuwaiti
daily Al-Watan is "totally baseless" and Khatami did not send any
message to Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran and Egypt are interested in improving their
relations and they are pacing the "natural course" of their ties.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Egypt severed their diplomatic relations after Tehran
accused Cairo of signing the Camp David peace accord with Israel,
the first one by an Arab country.
</P>
<P>
However, with the foreign policy of Iran's moderate President
Mohammad Khatami, Tehran and Cairo have improved bilateral
relations and cooperation, even though they have not resumed their
diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian officials have called on Iran to remove the hurdle for
the resumption of ties by changing the name of a main street in
Tehran, which was named after Khaled Islamboli, the assassin of
former Egyptian President Anwar Sadat in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said last month that the
 development of Tehran-Cairo ties during the past two years were
satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the relations between the two countries
will reach the highest level in the near future. 
</P>
