<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes Nazi Slave Labor Compensation Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Wednesday that the compensation for the Nazi slave labor
victims under a deal reached by U.S. and German negotiators
satisfies the requirements of people representing the victims of
the Nazi slave and forced labor.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the White House, Clinton said that
German Chancellor Gerhard Shroeder wrote to him to confirm that
the German government and German industry are prepared to commit
10 billion German marks, or more than 5 billion U.S. dollars to
fund slave and forced laborers under the Nazi regime.
</P>
<P>
A deal was reached Tuesday on the compensation after months of
negotiations by representatives from the U.S. and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Germany has already made about 60 billion U.S. dollars in
payments for war crimes, but there has never been compensation for
the Nazi era's estimated 12 million enslaved and forced workers.
</P>
<P>
The forced laborers would be paid between 2,600 and 3,125 U.S.
dollars and slave laborers who were held in concentration camps
would receive about 7,800 U.S. dollars each.
</P>
<P>
"We close the 20th century with an extraordinary achievement
that will bring an added measure of material and moral justice to
the victims of this century's most terrible crime," Clinton told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also lauded the German government. "This was not an
easy step for the German government to take," he said, adding that
"we could not have done this" without "truly remarkable leadership
" of Shroeder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
