<HEADLINE> Negotiations on Iranian Supply of Gas to Turkey Under                Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Energy Minister Cumhur
Ersumer said Turkey is negotiating with Iran on the implementation
of a deal under which Iran had pledged to start natural gas exports
to Turkey in two weeks, a local daily newspaper reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ersumer said Iran had delayed gas deliveries to Turkey under the
landmark 23-billion-U.S. dollars deal in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the deal, Turkey would initially buy 3 billion
cubic meters (bcms) of gas in 1999 from Iran through a pipeline
from Iran's Tabriz city to the Turkish capital Ankara.
</P>
<P>
A bit long ago, Iran promised to supply gas to the neighboring
country soon, but Ersumer expressed doubts on the timetable, saying
constructions of both the Turkish part of the pipeline and the
Iranian part are not ready yet.
</P>
<P>
Ersumer added that "we know Iran does not have the amount of gas
which it has pledged to us."
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that "negotiations are continuing, head of the
Turkish state pipeline company Botas will travel to Tehran next
week for further talks on the deal."
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the exports to Turkey will be another political
coup for Iran, which is looking to carry out such high-profile
deals to prove that the United States has failed to harm its
interests with the threat of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
For Turkey, the 1996 Turko-Iranian gas deal was heralded as
vital to its efforts to increase gas imports to meet demand which
is expected to rise to 15.8 bcms next year from 13 bcms this year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been trying to diversify its energy sources to ensure
its energy deficit closed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
