ANKARA -- Turkish Privatization Administration (OIB) has
announced that six local companies have placed bids to buy
government shares in two state-run insurance corporations.
</P>
<P>
The two insurance companies to be sold off are Ankara Sigorta
and Guven Sigorta. The OIB said that contenders would be allowed to
place bids in U.S. dollar terms, adding they would have to pay at
least 25 percent of their bids in cash, and the remaining 75
percent could be paid in equal installments over a maximum of three
years.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The London-based international rating agency Duff &AMP;
Phelps (DCR) has rated Turkish mobile phone operator Turkcell's
proposed bond issue at "BB-".
</P>
<P>
