<HEADLINE> Cambodia Strives to Improve Tourist Environment in Angkor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 16 (Xinhua) -- In an attempt to make the
temples of Angkor more attractive to tourists, Cambodian Apsara
Authority, a government tourism institution, took measures to ban
beggars and vendors from being around in the monuments there.
</P>
<P>
The government decided that no beggars shall be allowed on the
premises of Angkor Wat. It is a response to tourists' complaints
about being disturbed by the beggars.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is one of Cambodia's most promising industries and one
of the main foreign exchange earners.
</P>
<P>
The centuries-old Angkor Wat temples are regarded as some of
the world's most magnificent monuments and attract hundreds of
thousands of tourists every year.
</P>
<P>
The government's next step is to replace the pollutant
motorbikes and taxis with 300 battery-run electric cars that
officials hope will attract even more tourists.
</P>
<P>
In addition, airplanes will not allowed to fly over Angkor Wat
in order to protect the temples from damage by the strong sound
wave of the plane.
</P>
<P>
As the Tourism Minister Veng Seryvuth pointed out, Angkor Wat
is the heartland of the country, and a symbol of Cambodia's
tourism industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
