<HEADLINE> Estrada Orders Release of Political Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a press statement, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said
these alleged political offenders (APOs) were convicted for crimes
committed in pursuit of their political beliefs.
</P>
<P>
"The move was made in the spirit of the Yuletide season and in
support of the government's continuing and unilateral efforts to
undertake confidence-building measures for the promotion of the
peace process," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
He said President Estrada ordered the release of the APOs on
Wednesday after the Department of Justice (DOJ) recommended the
grant of conditional pardon to the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also approved the DOJ recommendation for the referral
of the cases of 40 more APOs to the Board of Pardons and Parole
because they were convicted for common crimes which were not
motivated by any political beliefs.
</P>
<P>
In signing the pardon papers of the APOs, Estrada stressed that
his administration will continue to pursue all efforts to push the
peace process forward, as well as to seek the release of
government personnel abducted by the New People's Army (NPA).
</P>
<P>
But the president also made it clear that police and military
units are more vigilant than ever to protect the public from
atrocities by armed rebels, like the NPA and the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front(MILF).
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government is now observing a suspension of
offensive military operations with the NPA. A cease-fire with the
MILF is also in effect pending the peace talks. 
</P>
