<HEADLINE> Pakistan Projects Growth Rate of Four Percent for 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Finance Minister
Shaukat Aziz Thursday projected over 4 percent growth rate during
the current fiscal in the backdrop of upbeat performance in the
agriculture and textile sector.
</P>
<P>
"The growth rate has been projected on the basis of emerging
economic situation," he told a press conference here while
explaining the features of the new economic agenda announced by
Chief Executive General Pervaiz Musharraf on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Flanked by other key economic officials, Aziz said in a
categorical term that the new government package was home-grown
and carved out without any pre-consultation with Bretton Woods
institutions.
</P>
<P>
General Musharraf Wednesday announced an economic revival plan
which is targeted at establishing a self-reliant economy.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister Abdul Razzaq Daud disclosed that country's
exports recorded 14 percent growth in November and the yearly
target of 9 billion U.S. dollars would likely to be surpassed.
</P>
<P>
Azuz said despite stable reserves position of the foreign
exchange, the pressure on balance of payment still persist as
trade deficit experienced 36 percent deterioration during the last
five months.
</P>
<P>
He did not rule out possibility of seeking further debt
rescheduling depending upon "the country's cash flow conditions".
"We will continue to review and re-profile the debt position," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Among the several initiatives taken in this respect, he said, a
high-level special committee has been constituted to study and
keep strict vigil on the country's debt profile.
</P>
<P>
He made a mention about the rescheduling arrangements already
made with the Paris Club, London Club and through exchange of
eurobonds, which totaled over 2.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the present rescheduling is available for period of
one to two years, adding that "if required by the cash flow
position, further rescheduling could be considered." 
</P>
</TEXT>
