<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estonian Parliament Passes Year 2000 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the budget, the main sources of revenue will be
the social tax (10.5 billion kroons, or 650 million dollars), the
turnover tax (7.6 billion kroons, or 490 million dollars), the
personal income tax (2.9 billion kroons, or 190 million dollars),
the fuel tax (1.8 billion kroons, or 120 million dollars), the
excise tax on alcohol (1.1 billion kroons, or 70 million dollars)
and the tax on tobacco (0.8 billion kroons, or 50 million dollars),
reported the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, revenues do not include corporate income
tax, which was canceled on Wednesday. The resulting deficit of 1.4
billion kroons (90 million dollars) should be covered by the
expected rise in other taxes and collections, a rise in duties and
economizing on government spending.
</P>
<P>
The priority items of spending are defense, education and
culture. The defense budget is expected to be raised from previous
1.4 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) to 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Estonian Prime Minister Mart Laar said the government is
determined to raise the figure to 2 percent of GDP by the year of
2002, which is the main condition of admission to the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
