<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh celebrates Victory Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The celebrations started with a 31-gun salute in the capital
city.
</P>
<P>
President Shahabuddin Ahmed and Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
placed wreaths at the National Mausoleum at Savar, on the
northwestern outskirts of the capital city, at dawn of the day to
pay respect to the memories of the martyrs.
</P>
<P>
As part of the celebrations, the president reviewed a combined
parade of the armed forces and other uniformed services, including
the police and the border force - the Bangladesh Rifles, at the
National Parade Square.
</P>
<P>
He also hosted a reception in the afternoon, which was attended
by government officials, politicians, diplomats and others.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the even of the day, the president called for
greater unity saying that the prime need of the hour was to forge
unity on important issues and create favorable social atmosphere
to ensure interrupted peace and development for the welfare of the
people.
</P>
<P>
The Victory Day in the national life rekindled new hopes and
aspirations for better living and thinking, he said. "We must give
preference to combating population increase, alleviation of
poverty and expanding technical education for economic development.
"
</P>
<P>
In a separate message, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina called for
taking vow on the day to build a poverty- and illiteracy-free
Bangladesh to face the challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The war of liberation was the greatest event in the history of
the Bengalees, she said.
</P>
<P>
Elaborate programs were organized to observe the day, which was
a public holiday, in the capital city and elsewhere in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
