<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Trade Promotion Yields Good Results: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held to brief the media on the
result of TDB's promotional and facilitation efforts, Ng Kim Neo,
Senior Director for Trade Policy, TDB, said "While the Asian
crisis clearly reinforced the importance of diversifying , it also
heightened many of our companies' foray into new and relatively
unexplored markets."
</P>
<P>
Ng said TDB is adopting a three-pronged approach to help
companies tap on such opportunities to further their overseas
expansion programs with focus on the renewed confidence in Asia,
riding the wave of business opportunities in established markets
and the need to continue diversifying into emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
According to TDB, it organized 92 fairs and missions to assist
more than 1,700 companies in their global expansion in 1999,
compared with 1,356 firms in 1998, and its promotion efforts to
strengthen Singapore's external trade wing has resulted in more
companies venturing overseas and returning to Asia to take
advantage of the business opportunities for trade and investment
arising from the improved economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
TDB officials said good result of their efforts has kept
Singapore to retain its position as the top ASEAN investor in
Malaysia,Indonesia, Thailand and the Philippines as well as the
largest foreign investor in Vietnam and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
On TDB's market development plans for 2000, senior TDB
officials said their board will leverage on renewed confidence in
Asia and enable companies to seize business opportunities the
economic recovery in Asia has presented in countries like Malaysia,
Thailand, the Philippines and Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
They confirmed that TDB will be organizing a high-level
business mission to Indonesia, Led by Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong,
as well as 27 more missions and fairs to the region in 2000.
</P>
<P>
They said TDB will also ride the wave of business opportunities
in the U.S., EU and China which are Singapore's important partners
with bilateral trade volume at 56.8, 43.8 and 13.1 billion
Singapore dollars (one U.S. dollar equals 1.68 Singapore dollars),
respectively in the first 10 months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
They said TDB plans to open a third Overseas Trade Office in
San Francisco, U.S., in view of Singapore companies' growing
presence in the U.S. and to help serve their needs better so as to
keep them closer to where the latest in cutting edge technology is
being developed and where new ideas are floated.
</P>
<P>
They said, TDB plans to organize 13 fairs and missions to the
EU to encourage Singapore companies from the IT, Sub-contracting,
logistics and franchising sectors to expand their presence in the
EU.
</P>
<P>
Noting China's impending accession to the WTO and its
significant advances in the field of biotechnology and precision
science, they said TDB will strengthen Sino-Singapore trade
further, help companies to collaborate with renowned Chinese
research institutions to commercialize their innovations and
intensify their efforts in key sectors such as telecommunications,
IT, e-commerce services and biotechnology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
