<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Leads The Way in Air Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Beijing, the Chinese national
capital, is close to reach its air pollution control target for
this year, said vice-mayor Wang Guangtao today.
</P>
<P>
During the first 11 months of this year, Beijing has cut
emissions of sulfur dioxide by 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
Two million tons of coal with less sulfur content have been
burned and several hundred million cubic meters of natural gas
have been used in the city, which is striving to make itself
cleaner and fresher.
</P>
<P>
At least 60,000 unworthy vehicles will be taken off the roads
and emission control devices will be installed in 110,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the total emission of
nitrogen oxide which is found in auto gas emissions has dropped by
five percent from the same period last year, while carbon monoxide
levels has dropped 10 percent. The level of suspended particles in
the air have been maintained due to large green belts around the
city.
</P>
<P>
Wang said it remains an arduous task to further improve the
quality of air in Beijing as the city still burns 25 million tons
of coal each year. Only 150,000 of the city's 1.4 million motor
vehicles are up to stringent environmental protection standards.
</P>
<P>
Wang vowed to continue the four-year pollution control
campaign Beijing launched a year ago by encouraging cleaner energy
alternatives and environment-friendly products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
