<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales in Britain Pick Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in Britain picked
up in November, when shoppers spent 0.2 percent more than in
October, leaving them 4.1 percent up from last year.
</P>
<P>
The increase was slightly less than analysts expected. The
Office for National Statistics (ONS) said Thursday the strong
retail sales trend has changed little from previous months.
</P>
<P>
The main forces driving the current increase were household
goods and "other stores" categories, the ONS added.
</P>
<P>
While the volume of goods sold continued to grow, the cash
earnings of shopkeepers failed to keep pace indicating that the
increase in retail sales is partly due to falling prices.
</P>
<P>
However, economists believe the strong retail sales figure is
another sign that the UK economy has recovered from the slowdown
that affected it earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
