<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Parliament Passes Fiscal 2000 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian National
Assembly on Thursday approved the country's fiscal 2000 budget,
putting emphasis on social services.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which was adopted after a four-day debate, with 89
votes in favor and 5 against, represented a 57 percent increase
from the 395 million U.S. dollars in fiscal 1999 to the 620
million dollars in fiscal 2000.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the budget for next year's rural development
and environment has doubled compared with 1999, and that for
education has climbed by 47 percent, while budget for public heath
has increased by 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
Spending on defense and security has been reduced from 3.8
percent to 3.5 percent of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP),
accounting for about 20 percent of the budget.
</P>
<P>
Prince Ranariddh, president of the National Assembly,
acknowledged that more cuts in military spending are needed, but
the allocation next year will mainly be used for soldiers' pay and
clothes and food, he said. "We hope there will be a true reduction
in military in next year,"the prince added.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh also said that the allocation for public investments,
such as road construction, are still less than expectations, while
the dependence on foreign aid is too much.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's GDP this year increased four percent from last year'
s one percent and is expected to grow a further 5.5 percent next
year,according to Finance Minister Keat Chhon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
