<HEADLINE> Russia Condemns NATO Statement on Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Russia Thursday rejected a
statement by NATO foreign ministers regarding Moscow's military
campaign against rebels in Chechnya as pointless, unacceptable and
amoral.
</P>
<P>
The statement, made Wednesday by the foreign ministers of the
alliance, was "pointless as far as the content goes, unacceptable
as far as the essence goes, and amoral as far as their authorship
goes," the Russian Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"The latest outpouring of crocodile tears in Brussels over
human rights (in Chechnya) is stunning in its wanton cynicism,"
the Interfax news agency quoted a Foreign Ministry report as
saying.
</P>
<P>
It said that by condemning Russia's operation in Chechnya, the
NATO generals, such as Supreme Commander Wesley Clark, attempted
to make the world forget the NATO air strikes against the
international TV centers and foreign embassies in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian Federation's internal affairs are not, cannot be,
and will not be the subject of international dialogue, especially
with NATO," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said Russia doubted the remark about restoring constructive
relations with Russia in the NATO statement. 
