<HEADLINE> Indian Parliament Passes Trade Mark Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- India's Rajya Sabha (Upper
House) Thursday passed the Trade Mark Bill 1999, which seeks to
make offenses cognizable and incorporate provisions in tune with
developments around the world.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which will replace the four-decade-old Trade and
Merchandise Act, was passed by a voice vote since opposition
members who proposed amendments did not move them.
</P>
<P>
Commerce and Industry Minister Murasoli Maran said that with
the help of the new act the government would strengthen trade mark
regulations in the country and clear backlog of trade mark
requests.
</P>
<P>
With the new legislation in place, the government will be in a
position to make best efforts to handle trade mark issues with
ease,he added.  
