<HEADLINE> Nigeria Reforms Educational System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government
Wednesday dissolved governing councils of 18 federally owned
universities as a part of its effort to reform the federal system
of education.
</P>
<P>
Some vice-chancellors and other high-ranking officials of the
universities are also to go in the days to come, the Guardian
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A reconstitution of the National Universities Commission was
also approved by the Federal Executive Council at its weekly
meeting in the Nigerian capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo, who is currently on a
four-day state visit to Germany, was represented by Vice-President
Atiku Abubakar at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Dapo Sarumi said after the meeting that
the measures followed recommendations raised by visitation panels
to probe activities of the universities.
</P>
<P>
Over two decades of relative obsolescence, obscurity and
general frustration in the universities are a sad fact in the
country, Sarumi said.
</P>
<P>
That was why 24 visitation panels to the universities were
formed, he added.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of 24 federally owned universities in
Nigeria.  
</P>
</TEXT>
