<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to Help Nigeria Get Back Looted Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Vice-President Atiku
Abubakar has urged the U.S. government to go the extra mile and
utilize its international influence to persuade European countries
to co-operate in getting back its looted money.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar made the call when meeting an eight-man U.S.
delegation by Undersecretary of State for Political Affairs Thomas
Pickering in Abuja Tuesday, the Guardian newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president told the U.S. officials that the Swiss
government has pledged to assist in the repatriation of 600
million U.S. dollars out of an estimated 2.5 billion dollars
stashed in that country's banks by Nigeria's former public
officials.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar also called on the U.S. to support and facilitate
Nigeria's move for debt forgiveness in view of the severe debt
over-hang which had been stalling infrastructure development in
the most populous African country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also canvassed more areas of cooperation and
assistance from the U.S. by way of huge investment, technical aid,
military training and facilities to be able to enhance the
on-going restructuring of the Nigerian military.
</P>
<P>
Pickering, in response, commended Nigeria's democratization
efforts by saying that the steps taken so far were cheering and
welcome.
</P>
<P>
Pledging U.S. commitment to working closely with Nigeria to
enhance its economic recovery, the U.S. official said his
government is increasingly focusing on Nigeria and "we would even
triple and quadruple our level of assistance to Nigeria in areas
of investment and technical assistance."
</P>
<P>
However, Pickering noted that there is need for the government
to take more practical steps to eliminate corruption in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
