<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Economy Out of "Intensive Care Unit" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The notorious traffic
nightmare is back, said Bangkokians. To make matters worse, they
said, more and more cars with red plates, which indicate that they
are bought within one month, appeared on the already crowded
streets in the Thai capital.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, red-plate cars have become the clearest sign of a hard-
fought economic recovery in the third year after the financial
storm hit the Southeast Asian "tiger" in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
With almost all of its foreign reserves depleted by the storm,
Thailand had to accept a 17.2 billion U.S. dollar rescue package
arranged by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) shortly after
the crisis broke out.
</P>
<P>
After two and a half years' fight, Thailand managed to bring
the international reserves to the present level of 32 billion
dollars, a level high enough to back the government's decision in
September to suspend drawing the remaining three billion dollars
from the IMF rescue funds.
</P>
<P>
At the height of the crisis, the Thai currency, the baht, fell
sharply from 26 baht to the dollar to as low as 55-56 baht.
</P>
<P>
But now, the baht has been stabilized at around 38 baht to the
greenback, with movement in quite a narrow range.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the country's external debts have been
reduced from 96 billion dollars to 80 billion, with debts of the
private sector being lowered from 70 billion dollars to 44 billion.
</P>
<P>
Despite steep drop of the baht's value, the Thais managed to
keep inflation under control since mid-1998. The inflation rate
now stands at about 0.5 percent, enabling interest rates to fall.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis brought down the Thai economy to a 10
percent contraction in the gross domestic products (GDP) in 1998,
but the economy successfully achieved a positive GDP growth of 0.9
percent and 3.5 percent, respectively, in the first and second
quarters of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Both Thai government officials and IMF representatives expected
a three to four percent GDP growth for the whole year of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The three economic stimulus packages launched by the government
in the past two years have been hailed as effective in helping
elevate the country's economic performance.
</P>
<P>
On August 14, 1998, the government introduced a comprehensive
financial reform package, helping local commercial banks to
recapitalize.
</P>
<P>
On March 30, 1999, the government implemented a 130-billion-
baht(3.5-billion-dollar) stimulus package, which was featured by
cuts of value-added tax and personal income tax and an increase of
budget deficit from five percent of the total GDP to six percent.
</P>
<P>
Nearly five months later, another package worth more than 100
billion baht (2.59 billion dollars) was introduced to spur the
exports and domestic demands by cutting import tariffs on some raw
materials and issuing bonds for potential home-buyers.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to all these packages, most of the "engines" of the Thai
economy, namely public spending, exports, domestic demands and
private investment, have resumed operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Lebanese Children Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen Lebanese children, all
under 10, were seriously wounded Thursday in a pro-Israel militia's
shelling on a south Lebanon school, security sources said.
</P>
<P>
The children were wounded when one of the mortar rounds fired by
the South Lebanon Army (SLA) hit their school in Arab Salim
village, which faces the Israeli-occupied border zone in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has confirmed that the shelling was launched by its ally
SLA, saying it aimed at retaliating earlier attacks from the same
village by guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of
God.
</P>
<P>
But Hezbollah denied that its fighters had launched any
operations on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After the incident, Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss issued a
statement strongly condemning the shelling.
</P>
<P>
"This is the latest Israeli aggression on Lebanon which was
added to the Jewish state's black record of attacks against
Lebanese civilians," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said Lebanon will file a complaint with the international
fire-ceasing committee which was set up in April 1996 after an
Israeli assault on Lebanon killing more than 200 people.
</P>
<P>
The five-nation group, made up of officers from the United
States, France, Syria, Lebanon and Israel, has been charged with
supervising the adherence of south Lebanon's belligerents to the
preclusion of civilian targets from warring parties.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, two Lebanese civilians were wounded in the
heaviest clash in recent months between Israeli forces and Lebanese
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The escalation of hostilities in south Lebanon came as Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa is in Washington along with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak for landmark negotiations aimed
at ending a half-century of conflicts between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Syrian Hezbollah's Secretary General Hassan Nasrallah
has said that despite the resumption of the Syrian-Israeli talks,
his group will not stop operations against Israeli occupation
forces until Israel pulls out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israelis out of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
