<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Economy Out of "Intensive-Care Unit" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
...and private investment, have resumed operation.
</P>
<P>
For public spending, the government, in the March 30 stimulus
package, allowed its budget deficit in the 1999 fiscal year to run
at six percent of the total GDP instead of the previous five
percent, offering more room for the expansion of public spending.
</P>
<P>
For exports, the country has seen a recovered growth after
years' recession beginning even before the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the first 11 months of this year, Thailand exported goods
worth 52.87 billion dollars, or a 6.1 percent increase from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Ministry officials expected that exports for the whole
year will grow by six percent from last year's 54.3 billion
dollars, exceeding the originally targeted four percent growth.
</P>
<P>
Domestic demands were also effectively prompted, which was best
demonstrated by the surge of automobile sales.
</P>
<P>
In the first 11 months of this year, some 181,134 cars were
sold, a 43.6 percent growth from the same period of last year. In
November alone, automobile sales reached 21,266 units, a record
high in 26 months.
</P>
<P>
Total automobile sales for the year are expected to exceed 200,
000, said Toyota Motor Thailand Ltd, which conducts the statistics
of the Thai automobile industry for the government.
</P>
<P>
The only engine that is not functioning so well is private
investment, which was curbed by a high level of non-performing
loans (NPLs) in local commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October, NPLs stood at 2.35 trillion baht (61
billion dollars), accounting for 43.39 percent of the total
outstanding loans of the entire Thai banking system.
</P>
<P>
Lamed by the NPLs, local banks are reluctant to extend new
loans, fearing that they will soon turn bad again.
</P>
<P>
This policy has made local enterprises, especially small- and
medium-sized ones, suffer since they depended heavily on bank
loans for their operation.
</P>
<P>
The government is trying hard to lower the NPL level by
accelerating the progress of debt restructuring and encouraging
local institutions to set up asset management companies to
separate bad loans from good ones.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry expected that NPLs will drop to 40 percent
by the end of this year and decrease further next year.
</P>
<P>
With the alleviation of the NPL trauma, the government hoped
that the Thai economy would grow by at least four percent next
year.
</P>
<P>
Some economists refuse to share the optimism of the government
on the rosy picture of the economy, saying great challenges are
still ahead.
</P>
<P>
They argue that the country's exports are likely to be
undermined by the expected fall of agricultural products next year
and there is little room for the government to expand state
spending since the public debts will reach a peak at 60 percent of
GDP next year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the differences, one opinion commonly agreed is that
the ailing Thai economy has been unmistakably out of the "
intensive-care unit."
</P>
<P>
Both the optimists and the pessimists agreed that apart from
short-term measures to steer the economy, long-term structural
adjustment is also urgently needed as the recovery is still
fragile.
</P>
<P>
They said reforms in Thailand's legal system, government
agencies and state enterprises are necessary in order to guarantee
the country a higher degree of competitiveness in the "post-crisis
" era. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
