<HEADLINE> 11th Session of Final-status Talks postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The 11th session of final-
status negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians, scheduled
for Thursday morning, were postponed till Sunday morning, Israel
Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian negotiation team asked for the delay because its
chief negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo is sick, according to the
report. There are no details about Rabbo's sickness.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts claimed that the Palestinians put off the
talks in order to observe and evaluate the latest progress of the
Israeli-Syrian track.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the resumption of Israeli-Syrian
talks Wednesday in Washington worried the Palestinians because they
are afraid that any progress of the Syrian track would divert
attention from the Israeli-Palestinian talks and make the them more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
The final-status talks' last session was held Monday at the Erez
checkpoint after last week's incident, in which the Palestinians
threatened to suspend the talks to protest against Jewish
settlement activities in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
With the mediation of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, the Palestinians at last decided to resume the talks, but
to keep the settlement issue on top of the agenda. 
</P>
