<HEADLINE> Three Japanese Telecom Firms to Merge Next October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Three Japanese telecom firms,
DDI Corp., IDO Corp. and KDD Corp., announced Thursday that they
have signed a memorandum to merge into a single company on October
1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The merger will create Japan's second largest
telecommunications company, following the group led by Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone Corp. (NTT).
</P>
<P>
DDI is a long-distance carrier belonging to the Kyocera Corp.
Group, while IDO is a mobile phone operator affiliated with
Japan's largest auto maker Toyota Motor Corp. KDD is the country's
largest international telecom carrier, with Toyota as a major
shareholder.
</P>
<P>
Under the "KDDI" logo, the new firm will provide comprehensive
services for domestic, international and mobile phones, the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
DDI President Yusai Okuyama will assume the presidency of the
new firm, while Kazuo Inamori, honorary chairman of Kyocera, and
Toyota Chairman Hiroshi Okuda will be the honorary chairmen.
</P>
</TEXT>
