<HEADLINE> HK's Economy Turns Around </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's economic
prospects now look excellent, said a senior Hong Kong financial
official Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mike Rowse, director of the business and services promotion
unit of the financial secretary's Office, made the conment on the
results of the 1999 Business Outlook Survey conducted by the
American Chamber of Commerce (AmCham) in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's economic prospects now look excellent. As we have
said all along, our sound fundamentals will show through in time.
Clearly the Amcham members share our view that the worst is over,"
Rowse said.
</P>
<P>
He said this was further evidence that the economy had turned
around.
</P>
<P>
He was encouraged by the fact that an overwhelming majority of
the survey respondents (as many as 84 percent of the 393 AmCham
members companies that responded) perceived a "good" or "
satisfactory" outlook in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, the positive outlook for our economy is also widely
shared by the international community," Rowse said.
</P>
<P>
The continuous confidence in Hong Kong's business environment
is evidenced by the fact that 81 percent of the 75 percent of
companies that have regional headquarters in Hong Kong said they
would retain their regional base and one third of them said they
intended to expand their operations.
</P>
<P>
In assessing the business environment in Hong Kong, respondents
said that the five most satisfactory aspects of doing business in
Hong Kong are: geographical location, taxation system, free port
status, communication network and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will continue to provide a positive environment for
people to do business," Rowse said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
