<HEADLINE> HK to Enhance Economic Relations with Macao: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa
Thursday said that Hong Kong will further enhance the economic
cooperation with Macao after its return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Tung said the future cooperation between Hong Kong and Macao is
promising. The cooperative projects will be planned in tourism
industry and joint efforts will be made to develop the area of
Pearl River Delta with Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference this afternoon, Tung said that
the concept of "One Country, Two Systems" has been well-
implemented in Hong Kong in all aspects of life over the past two
and a half years, adding that he believes that it will also be
well-implemented in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Tung said he is optimistic about the future of Macao and the
success of the reunification of the motherland since what Hong
Kong has done over the past years proved that the concept of "One
Country, Two Systems" is correct and powerful.
</P>
<P>
"China's resumption of sovereignty over Macao is the pride of
the nation and it is very precious opportunity to witness another
celebration of historical significance," Tung said. He will attend
the ceremony to be held in Macao on December 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's experience must be helpful to the newly-born Macao'
s SAR government, Tung said, adding that "on one hand, we must
spare no effort to maintain the two systems, and on the other we
must be active in helping the Hong Kong people know more about the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, the Hong Kong SAR government has played an
important role in the construction of Hong Kong's economy,
especially in infrastructure, including the construction of
airport, roads and tourism facilities, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"The government should help create favorable environment for
local people to display their talents and capacity," he said. "In
addition to the hardware, we have helped create favorable software
environment, including investment in education and living
environment."  
</P>
</TEXT>
