<HEADLINE> UNFICYP Mandate Extended for Another Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
passed late Wednesday night a resolution extending the U.N.
Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) mandate for another six
months, the Cyprus News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The resolution reaffirmed all previous U.N. resolutions on
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
U.S. resolutions called for a Cyprus settlement based on a state
 of Cyprus with a single sovereignty and international personality
and a single citizenship, comprising two politically equal
communities in a bi-communal and bi-zonal federation.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council noted in its UNFICYP resolution that the
Cyprus government "has agreed that in view of the prevailing
conditions in the island it is necessary to keep the UNFICYP in
Cyprus beyond December 15, 1999."
</P>
<P>
The UNFICYP mandate is extended for a further six-month period
ending June 15, 2000 and U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan is
requested "to submit a report by June 1, 2000 on the implementation
 of this resolution."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when the
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island following a short-lived coup, engineered by the then Greek
Junta against late President Archbishop Makarios.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the UNFICYP troops have been patrolling along the
dividing line separating the Turkish troops and the Greek Cypriot
National Guards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China In Sprint At Finish To Clear Up Major Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China has been sprinting to
finish the clean-up of one of its major lakes, Chaohu in Anhui
Province, as all industrial enterprises around the freshwater lake
must meet state pollutant discharge standards by the end of 1999
as scheduled to meet the requirements by the State Council.
</P>
<P>
This was announced recently by Huang Yuezhong, vice-governor of
the province.
</P>
<P>
Clearing up Chaohu Lake, one of China's five largest freshwater
lakes, is one of the nation's largest environmental protection
projects.
</P>
<P>
Chaohu Lake has been threatened by serious pollution and
dwindling wetlands for the past several years because of rapid
industrial development and advancing urbanization around the lake.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 280 million tons of industrial sewage and that
created by nearby residents flows into the lake every year, and
the region around the lake, 13,000 square kilometers, suffers from
serious soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
Work to control pollution on the lake is progressing smoothly,
and of the leading 109 enterprises around it, each producing more
than 100 tons of waste water per day, 85 have reached state
emission standards and 14 have been shut down, moved or changed to
other production. The remaining 10 are working hard to reach the
goal as scheduled. All these endeavors have so far cost 227
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, of the 162 enterprises that each produce fewer
than 100 tons of waste water, 120 have completed pollutant
treatment.
</P>
<P>
Anhui has used 140 million US dollars of loans from the Asian
Development Bank, and six million US dollars of loans from foreign
governments to build sewage disposal plants and facilities in
cities located in the lake region.
</P>
<P>
A project to clean out silt deposited in the lake bed, which
fills with more than two million tons of silt and mud annually
from the shrinking wetlands and banks around the lake, has
recently been approved.
</P>
<P>
Chaohu Lake is on a major migration route between Australia and
China used by many wading birds, and is also a winter haven for
200 species of migratory birds.
</P>
<P>
Because of the existing serious pollution, fewer migratory
birds and fishermen are now found at the lake, which is also
filled with withering reeds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Stocks 1.60 Percent Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks ended down
253.95 points, or 1.60 percent, to close at 15,571.36 Thursday,
amid dwindling liquidity as institutions squared their books for
1999.
</P>
<P>
The turnover Thursday was 9.676 billion HK dollars (1.24
billion U.S. dollars), 2.064 billion HK dollars (265 million U.S.
dollars) down from Wednesday's 11.74 billion HK dollars (1.5
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
All the four sub-indices saw losses, with Finance dropping by 2.
23 percent while Utilities, Properties and Commerce &AMP; Industry
lost 1.27 percent, 0.54 percent and 1.63 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index was up 1.46 percent and
Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporations Index up 0.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stocks dropped down 10.73 points, or 0.06 percent, to
open at 15,814.58 Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
