<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Talks to Examine Cyprus Parties' Positions: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Foreign Minister Ioannis
 Kasoulides has said the second round of the U.N.-sponsored
proximity talks on Cyprus is to examine in depth the positions of
the two Cypriot communities.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus News Agency (CNA) reported Thursday that Kasoulides
said the talks, scheduled to take place in Geneva from January 27
until February 6, 2000, will try to ascertain common ground on
various points, already discussed in the first round.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that he was encouraged by the fact that the
talks to be continued in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash started proximity talks in New York on December 3-14,
 under the U.N. auspices, to find a solution for the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriots
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island in reaction to a failed coup in
Nicosia seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides predicted that there would be no deadlock in the next
 round as no agreement is anticipated to be concluded in Geneva, an
 objective expected to be achieved at a later phase of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister noted that many issues relating to Cyprus
and Turkey have now been placed under the scrutiny of the European
Union (EU), as both countries are now candidates for accession.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Turkish Cypriot leader to swim with the flow. "
Today's circumstances and conjunctures, relating to the Helsinki
summit and Greco-Turkish relations, are such that enable us to make
 every possible effort to seek a settlement in Cyprus," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
