<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Auditors Play Bigger Role in Anti-Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Signs show that China's
auditors are now playing a bigger role in the country's anti-
corruption drive.
</P>
<P>
Auditor General Li Jinhua announced here today that auditors
have so far this year audited 112,000 institutions, saving losses
up to 29.8 billion yuan and discovering 1,458 cases of
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
He made the disclosure at a press conference sponsored by the
Press Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
At the 10th meeting of the Standing Committee of the National
People Congress last June, the auditors made their first shocking
disclosure about the serious misuse of funds by the ministries of
Finance and Water Resources and other government departments.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, 1.8 billion yuan of the misused funds have
been recovered, while some of the office and hotel buildings built
with misused funds have been confiscated for auction.
</P>
<P>
Persons involved in these cases have received in-Party or
administrative sanctions, while some others are under
investigation by the Ministry of Supervision, the auditor general
said.
</P>
<P>
For the fourth year, the auditors reviewed the implementation
of the government budget this year and found some serious problems,
most of which have been or are being corrected.
</P>
<P>
In auditing the Commerce and Industry Bank of China and the
Construction Bank of China, the auditors found that their
management and loan quality have greatly improved, but there is
still much to be done.
</P>
<P>
"Bad loans account for more than 10 percent of the banks' total
loans in many cases, some even higher," the auditor general said.
</P>
<P>
Auditing was also done in 45 large and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises (SOEs), leading to the discovery of false financial
reports on assets and liabilities and the loss of state-owned
assets.
</P>
<P>
In the first 11 months, the auditors audited 17,000 officials
at county level and SOE leaders. About 10 percent of them were
found to have problems for which they were demoted or further
investigated, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The auditors also played an important role in the
investigations of 28 major economic criminal cases by providing
evidence found in their auditing work.
</P>
<P>
Among them are the stock market fraud case involving the Daqing
Lianyi Co., Ltd. and serious smuggling cases in Zhanjiang City of
Guangdong Province in south China.
</P>
<P>
The auditor general said the work of the auditors clearly shows
the Chinese government's determination to crack down on corruption
and improve the transparency of the economic system.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the auditors would next year focus on the
auditing of the government budget implementation, financial
management of enterprises and banking organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, DPRK to Hold Preparatory Talks in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Japan and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) will hold preparatory government-
level talks on normalizing diplomatic ties next Monday and Tuesday
in Beijing, Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Mikio Aoki announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday and next Monday, the Red Cross societies of both
countries will also meet in the Chinese capital to discuss
humanitarian issues, the top Japanese government spokesman told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
Government officials of the two countries will attend the
meetings of the Red Cross societies, Aoki said.
</P>
<P>
The move came after Tokyo announced Tuesday that it will lift
its freeze on food aid to Pyongyang and plans to restart
negotiations on normalizing diplomatic ties, removing the last of
a series of sanctions imposed after the DPRK fired a rocket over
Japan last August.
</P>
<P>
Talks on normalizing ties between the Japan and the DPRK began
in January 1991, but collapsed after eight rounds in November 1992.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed in August 1998 to restart the talks,
but Tokyo froze the initiative after Pyongyang launched later that
month a multistage rocket, part of which flew over Japan into the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo and Pyongyang saw a thaw in their bilateral ties after a
visit to Pyongyang earlier this month by former Japanese Prime
Minister Tomiichi Murayama and a nonpartisan mission of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese mission agreed with the DPRK's Workers' Party of
Korea to urge their respective governments to resume talks on
normalizing bilateral diplomatic ties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's November Consumer Price Index Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 16 (Xinhua)-- Israel's consumer price index
(CPI) posted a 0.2 percent drop in November, enough to fuel
expectations of a sizable drop in interest rate later but not
enough for economists to revise their inflation forecast for next
year.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of 1999, the CPI has only risen 1.3 percent
and for the whole 1999 it is expected to close at about 1.5
percent, according to figures issued by the Central Bureau of
Statistics (CBS) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Bank of Israel, the central bank, is expected to
lower interest rates next month by 0.5 percent, and local
economists forecast that inflation rate for next year is expected
to be less than 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
November's decline reflected a seasonal reduction in product
prices and a fall in prices in the housing sector. The drop was
partially offset by a seasonal rise in clothing and footwear
prices.
</P>
<P>
November's price changes covered such sectors as food, up by
only 0.1 percent, fruit and vegetables, down by 2.6 percent,
housing, down by 1.2 percent, housing service, down by 1.3 percent,
 while clothing and footwear, up by 4.4 percent and health, up by
0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Wholesale Price Index for industrial production for domestic
 use rose by 0.1 percent in November, and prices for housing starts
 fell by 0.1 percent too.
</P>
<P>
The Manufacturers' Association said that 1999's low rate and
expectations of lower inflation in 2000 will enable Israel's
industrial sector to undertake a number of steps to maintain
sustainable growth, to implement reforms in direct taxation and to
change monetary and fiscal policies in order to lay the foundation
for long-term growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0186 </DOCNO>
