<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges Turkey to Pull Out From Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has condemned "fresh
Turkish aggression" on its northern territories and urged Ankara to
 pull out its troops immediately.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said Thursday that on November 30, another 1,000
Turkish soldiers entered into northern Iraq's Kanimasi area.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified Foreign Ministry spokesman said that with the
support of tanks, heavy artillery and helicopters, other Turkish
armed troops already stationed in northern Iraq continued their
military aggression against Iraqi territories.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq absolutely rejects the flimsy pretexts Turkey has
used to justify its repeated aggressions against Iraqi territories.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has claimed that its military operations in northern Iraq
 are aimed at cracking down on outlawed rebels of Turkish Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) who have been fighting for independence since
1984.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Turkey's new aggression coincided with the
aggressive military acts carried out by the U.S. and Britain
against Iraq to interfere in its internal affairs and to perpetuate
 the abnormal status in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes coming from Turkish airspace patrol
the northern no-fly zone in Iraq set up following the 1991 Gulf War
 with the claimed aim of protecting the Iraqi Kurds there against
possible attacks by Iraqi government troops.
</P>
<P>
After the Gulf War, Baghdad lost control over the northern
Kurdish autonomous region, and Turkish government troops often
launched cross-border offensives against rebels of PKK who have
been seeking shelters there.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq holds Turkey responsible for the consequences of its
repeated aggressive acts and violation of Iraq's sovereignty and
territorial integrity," warned the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
