<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Unveils Previously Undisclosed 163 Aircraft Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Co., the world's
largest airplane maker, Wednesday unveiled 163 aircraft orders,
boosting its total for 1999 to 368 orders, according to reports
from the company.
</P>
<P>
Boeing said the 163 orders, worth 9.5 billion U.S. dollars, had
not been disclosed before at the request of customers. The
announcement from the company's commercial airplanes division also
includes a 2.6 billion-dollar-order for 20 airplanes placed by
General Electric Co.'s GE Capital Aviation Services unit.
</P>
<P>
Boeing said it has adopted an industry-wide practice and is
counting all orders, including those placed by customers who wish
to remain unidentified.
</P>
<P>
Until now, policy has prevented Boeing from announcing any firm
orders until the buyer can be named. Airlines and other buyers
don't want their orders revealed for competitive, financing or
strategic reasons.
</P>
<P>
However, rival Airbus Industries, the European aerospace
consortium, already includes certain orders from unnamed customers
in its totals.
</P>
<P>
Boeing's move appears designed to reduce Airbus's huge lead in
jet orders for this year. Airbus has about 417 firm orders so far,
nearly a 60 percent share of the companies' combined total.
</P>
<P>
Of the 163 plane orders by unidentified customers, 132 are for
737s, 14 for 757s, 12 for 767s, four 777s and one 747.
</P>
<P>
The company said it expects to end the year with a record
delivery of about 620 jetliners, compared with 563 deliveries last
year. However, Boeing expects its production to drop by about 23
percent to about 480 planes in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Announcement of previously unidentified orders aims at boosting
the company's competitive image, industry sources said. The
posturing over order totals is part of an annual ritual that has
become more meaningful as Airbus has become a stronger rival for
Boeing.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. jet maker once dominated at least two-thirds of orders
and sales by every measure. Orders are an indication of future
sales and revenue, but the totals can be deceiving. Orders are
often canceled or delayed when airlines weaken financially.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
