<HEADLINE> Iraq to Restart Oil Exports on Friday: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Iraq is planning to restart its
 oil exports to world markets on Friday under the newly-approved
seventh phase of the oil-for-food program, an Iraqi daily reported
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Ath-Thawra daily, of the ruling Baath party, quoted an
unnamed official as saying that the implementation of the plan
depends on the approval of Iraq's oil contracts by the U.N.
Sanctions Committee and the arrival of oil tankers at the Turkish
Ceyhan port and southern Iraq's Bakr oil terminal.
</P>
<P>
Under relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions, Iraq's
contracts for selling oil and importing goods must first be
approved by the U.N. Sanctions Committee before any shipment can be
 made.
</P>
<P>
The official said that Iraq had started to sign contracts on
Monday with foreign companies to sell crude oil under the new phase
 of the humanitarian program.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council last Friday unanimously approved a
six-month extension of the program which allows Iraq to sell 5.2
billion U.S. dollars worth of oil to buy food, medicine and other
relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
The program was designed to alleviate the suffering of Iraqi
people reeling under the stringent U.N. sanctions imposed since
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraq halted its oil exports on November 24 to protest over a
two-week extension of the sixth phase of the oil-for-food deal
which expired on November 20.
</P>
<P>
The halt continued and the Security Council extended the program
 for an additional week after the first two-week extension expired.
</P>
<P>
Iraq insisted that it needed a normal six-month rollover of the
program in order to plan properly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
