<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Western Reports of Its Heavy Loss in Grozny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Russian military Thursday
categorically denied Western media reports on heavy losses of a
Russian armored column last night in Grozny, capital of the
rebellious Chechen republic.
</P>
<P>
Western media earlier reported that over 100 Russian soldiers
were killed during a Wednesday night battle in Grozny, when
thousands of Chechen rebels surrounded the federal troops and
pounded them with rocket-propelled grenades.
</P>
<P>
The battle scene, a square near central Grozny, was littered
with the bodies of the dead and blazing armored vehicles, said a
Reuters report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev Thursday
called the reports "an information provocation," stressing that "
there was no assault and there will be no assault on Grozny."
</P>
<P>
"We are to find out who has launched this information
provocation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Defense Ministry's press service Thursday denied
the Western reports about an attempt by Russian troops to storm
Grozny last night.
</P>
<P>
Colonel General Valery Manilov, first deputy chief of the
Russian General Staff, also stated that the Russian federal
command did not launch any assault on Grozny last night.
</P>
<P>
"Reports about the defeat of a Russian armored column by the
rebels in Grozny's Minutka Square are lies and misinformation," he
told press Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
"No Russian armored vehicles have entered the city" and Grozny
"will not be stormed until civilians are evacuated," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Russian Federal Security Service's Public
Relations Center, General Alexander Zdanovich, said Thursday that
the reports "may be deliberate misinformation."
</P>
<P>
"I do not rule out that the spreading of such reports is a
special move, made on the eve of the parliamentary elections in
Russia in order to put pressure on the government and blame it for
poorly-planned actions in Chechnya," Zdanovich said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that most of the foreign agencies' correspondents in
Grozny are Chechens. Some of them may have sent out such reports
under the pressure of the rebels, while others are connected with
the Chechen special services, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
