<HEADLINE> Iran Not to Air Film on Confession of Serial Murders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A special committee has advised
the Iranian authorities not to air the film on the confessions of
those involved in the serial killings of Iranian opposition leaders
 and dissident writers.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Tehran Times on Thursday quoted an unidientified
source as saying that Iranian President Mohammad Khatami formed a
four-member special committee on behalf of the Supreme National
Security Council to decide whether it is advisable to air the film
or not.
</P>
<P>
"After watching the film, the committee advised that the film
should not be broadcast on the TV, but gave no specific reasons,"
the source said.
</P>
<P>
The Judicial Organization of the Iranian armed forces has
promised to broadcast the film through the state-run television in
November.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the daily quoted Intelligence Minister Ali Yunesi as
saying that the film had some problems which should be removed.
</P>
<P>
In November and December last year, the leader of the Iran
Nation Party Darius Forouhar and his wife were stabbed to death at
home and at least three dissident writers were mysteriously killed
in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Intelligence Ministry announced in January that some of
its own agents were involved in the political murders. The
revelation triggered a sharp political quarrel between the
conservative and moderate factions and forced former Intelligence
Minister Qorbanali Dorri Najafabadi to resign.
</P>
<P>
Former Deputy Intelligence Minister for Political and Security
Affairs Saeed Emami was believed to be the mastermind behind the
political killings. But Emami committed suicide in prison June by
taking in depilatory substance while taking a bath.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Judicial Organization of the Iranian armed forces
Mohammad Niazi said earlier that a total of 23 people have been
arrested in connection of the political killings while 33 others
have been summoned for investigations.
</P>
<P>
However, local media believed that Emami was not the highest
agent behind the political killings, because he had no right to
issue religious verdicts against dissident writers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
