<HEADLINE> No Attack Expected in Turkey Against American Targets: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish officials said they do
not expect any terrorist attack against U.S. targets by Bin Laden's
 followers in the country, Turkish Daily News reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish intelligence sources said that small groups linked with
Laden's network did operate in Turkey, primarily in Istanbul and
Ankara, but these groups were involved exclusively in spreading the
 words of Islam, unlikely to attack U.S. targets in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Bin Laden, a Saudi-born millionaire who is reportedly living in
a secret hideout under Afgan Taliban protection, was charged by the
 U.S. of masterminding the twin bombings of American embassies in
Africa last year.
</P>
<P>
Recently, anxiety over the possibility of U.S. citizens in
Turkey being targeted by Ladan's followers has emerged after the U.
S. State Department warned its citizens abroad of possible
terrorist attacks by Laden during celebrations of the Christmas,
Ramadan and New Year.
</P>
<P>
Turkish intelligence sources said that so far there had been no
arrests made on Laden's followers as no evidence has been found on
these groups' involvement in any crime.
</P>
<P>
The sources stressed, however, that the Turkish intelligence
agency is keeping them under close scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
U.S. sources here said the warning was worldwide and that no
additional precautions had been taken regarding U.S. facilities in
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
