<HEADLINE> Iran Voices Readiness to Export Gas to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- An official from the Iranian
National Oil Company has voiced Tehran's readiness to export gas to
 Ankara according to a deal concluded in 1996, local daily Iran
News reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to dispatch our experts to help Turkey in making
preparations which has become urgent with the advent of winter,"
the unnamed official said in an interview with the daily.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the Turkish side appears not quite ready to
import 2 billion cubic meters of gas for the first year of the
contract, but it will be able to import 1 billion cubic meters
instead.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, Turkey will pay 20 billion dollars for
buying gas from Iran in the next 25 years, some 2 billion cubic
meters of gas in the first year and the volume will be increased to
 10 billion cubic meters by 2006.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official said that Iran is putting finishing touches
 to its natural gas pipeline link-up with Turkey, enabling it to
embark on transferring its natural gas to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The length of gas pipeline in Iranian territory is about 260
kilometers while in Turkey about 300 kilometers, he said, adding
that head of the Turkey's pipeline company Botas would visit Iran
next week to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's increasing gas consumption will reach 15.8 billion
cubic meters in 2000 and may approach 55 billion cubic meters in
2010, Iran News said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
