<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Dollar Strengthens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand dollar has
strengthened Thursday on the back of news that the New Zealand
government and the New Zealand central bank, the Reserve Bank,
have signed a new anti-inflation agreement.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that new Finance Minister Michael Cullen and
Reserve Bank Governor Don Brash have agreed on changes to
instructions for keeping inflation between zero and three percent.
</P>
<P>
The one significant change now states: "In pursuing its price
stability objective, the Bank shall implement monetary policy in a
sustainable, consistent and transparent manner and shall seek to
avoid unnecessary instability in output, interest rates and the
exchange rate."
</P>
<P>
The change means the Reserve Bank is now required to avoid
unnecessary instability in the economy, the currency and interest
rates, as it keeps inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
Minister Cullen said the change aims to stop the Reserve Bank
repeating its policy of the mid-90s, which saw the New Zealand
dollar rise damaging the export sector.
</P>
<P>
Governor Brash said he did not seek the change, but
nevertheless welcomed it, as it makes explicit the way monetary
policy in New Zealand has been evolving in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He said as the credibility of the monetary framework in New
Zealand continues to be further enhanced, so "instability in
output, interest rates and the exchange rate" should further
decline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
