<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PC to Remain Dominant Online Appliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Nine in 10 American homes
will be online in five years, while personal computers will remain
the dominant Internet access terminal, according to a study
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Most homes will use a number of non-PC online appliances, but
PC won't be replaced, said the study of Strategy Analytics, a U.S.
market consulting business in high- technology.
</P>
<P>
By 2005, according to the study, 91 percent of American homes
will be online, 90 percent of them will be using an Internet PC,
73 percent will also have interactive TV or other Internet
appliances.
</P>
<P>
Online TV-based set-top boxes will become commonplace in
American homes. Limited demand also exists for a range of new
Internet terminals that are independent of the PC or TV, such as
screephones and Web terminals. Sales of such devices will reach
600 million U.S. dollars in 2005.
</P>
<P>
Sales of interactive TV appliances, such as online digital TV
set-top boxes and advanced games consoles, will reach 2.4 billion
dollars in 2002. Sales will peak at 4.8 billion dollars in 2003,
before declining to 4.2 billion dollars in 2005 under the impact
of falling prices. Shipments, however, are expected to reach 7.4
million units in 2000 and 26.4 million units by 2005.
</P>
<P>
On average, a U.S. online home will have 2.7 online devices by
2005, according to the study. This represents an emerging
opportunity for Internet service providers and network operators.
</P>
<P>
According to the research company Yankee Group, approximately
650,000 U.S. homes have some form of networking installed now, and
the number is expected to grow at a compound annual growth rate of
95 percent over the next four years, when it will reach 10 million
by 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
