<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Sell Foreign Loan Assets by Tender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Pengurusan
Danaharta Nasional Bhd (Danaharta) (National Assets Management
Corporation) Thursday announced the sale by restricted tender of
foreign loan assets.
</P>
<P>
The assets comprise nine non-ringgit loans and 14 marketable
securities extended to or issued by foreign companies, it said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
It said five principal bidders and 16 marketable account
bidders had been pre-selected to participate in the restricted
tender for 251.7 million U.S. dollars in principal value of
foreign loan assets.
</P>
<P>
The principal bidders are Credit Suisse First Boston, Dresdner
Kleinwort Benson, JP Morgan, Lehman Brothers and Salomon Smith
Barney while the marketable account bidders, like the principal
bidders, are pre-selected investment banks, financial institutions
and securities and brokerage houses ordinarily engaged in
securities dealing, it said.
</P>
<P>
The tender will close on February 22, 2000, and the results are
targeted to be finalized two days after the close of the tender,
it said, adding the tender would be audited by Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
The information memorandum on the tender will be available on
its website at www.danaharta.com.my from Friday for reference only,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Danaharta, a special mechanism set up by the government last
year to deal with non-performing loans and troubled corporate
assets, has to date a total of 594.4 million U.S. dollars in
principal value of foreign loan assets.
</P>
<P>
The agency employs various strategies in disposing of its
foreign loan assets and a sale by restricted tender is one of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
