<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Syrian and Israeli negotiation teams held
about 80 minutes of talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright attendance at the U.S. official guest house, Blair House,
on Wednesday after an opening ceremony at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The talks then adjourned until Thursday's 11:00 a.m. (1600 GMT).
No substantive details of the talks were released because of
effective news blackout for the two days of negotiations. White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart told a briefing after the Blair House
meeting at 4:30 p.m. (2130 GMT) that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara discussed with
Albright how to move toward a peace agreement, which Middle East
experts believe could not be reached until the settlement of the
dispute over the Golan Heights, the Syrian territory snatched by
Israel during the 1967 six-day war. (US-Israel-Syria)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said Wednesday
that he and U.S. President Bill Clinton had agreed on a fund of 10
billion marks (4.7 billion U.S. dollars) to compensate millions of
slave laborers during Germany's Nazi era, ending year-long
negotiations on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said he and Clinton had agreed both on the sum and
measures to protect German firms against new legal demands for
further compensations on the issue. The chief U.S. negotiator,
Deputy Secretary of Treasury Stuart Eizenstat, flew to Berlin on
Wednesday evening in an effort to hammer out with his German
counterpart Otto Graf Lambsdorff the details of a final German-U.S.
solution that will be signed on Friday at the G-8 Foreign
Ministers' meeting here. (Germany-US-Nazi Labor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- Romania's largest opposition party Wednesday
repeated its appeal for a legal solution to the current government
crisis caused Tuesday by President Emil Constantinescu's order to
remove Prime Minister Radu Vasile.
</P>
<P>
Ion Iliescu, chairman of the Romanian Social Democracy Party,
stressed in the appeal that the country's law gives only the
parliament, not the president, the authority to sack the prime
minister, and therefore urged the president and the ruling
coalition to "correct their error." He told the press that the
crisis can be resolved properly only by a parliamentary vote of no-
confidence on the government given Vasile's refusal to resign. But
first of all, the president should retract his order, which is
unconstitutional, he demanded. (Romania-Government Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The Export-Import Bank of Korea has agreed to supply a
loan of 3.22 billion U.S. dollars to the Korea Peninsula Energy
Development Organization (KEDO) for the construction of light-
water reactors in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK),
the bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the loan will be earmarked for the
construction of two light-water nuclear reactors, which the United
States, South Korea and Japan have agreed on to ease tensions on
the Korean Peninsula. The loan will be extended on an interest-
free basis, while the principal should be repaid in six-month
installments over 20 years, including a three-year grace period,
after the completion of two reactors, said the bank. (SKorea-DPRK-
Nuclear Actor) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
