<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lake in East China Attracts 2,400 Geese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A lake on the outskirts of
Rongcheng, a coastal city in east China's Shandong Province, has
drawn some 2,400 brants, a variety of goose, which are now living
there together with thousands of rare birds including swans, other
wide geese, and grey cranes.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of 2,398 brants now at the lake, according to
Lu Jianjian, a waterfowl expert.
</P>
<P>
Brants are entirely black except for a ring of white feathers
on their necks. The birds eat seaweed, and are very rare, and at
one time were found only in Japan, said the expert.
</P>
<P>
Due to the environmental protection efforts of the local
government, many more rare birds now inhabit the lake.
</P>
<P>
The lake currently has become a paradise for tens of thousands
of birds, many of them rare, Lu noted.
</P>
<P>
The city also has carried out environment-friendly renovations
of 80 industrial projects which caused pollution in recent years,
and a paper mill and 17 fishmeal plants were shut down.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the city has set up a sewage treatment system,
handling some 20,000 tons of sewage per day. In addition, ten
stations supervising the marine environment now have been set up
in Rongcheng. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
