<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao on Track of Economy Recovery (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Macao reported a foreign trade
volume of 25.4 billion patacas in the first ten months of this
year, an increase of 4.7 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, Macao's exports in September was
up by 16.7 percent over the same previous month, indicating that
Macao is well on track of a fairly fast economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Though the export-oriented Macao economy saw negative growth in
1998 under the negative influence of the Asia financial crisis, it
is now recovering with vigor thanks to a timely restructuring and
improved confidence of investors in the future of post-return
Macao.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, the inflow of overseas funds
has pick up speed, with Macao's foreign exchange reserve swelling
to nearly 20 billion patacas, ten times the figure eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
At present, banks from Britain, the United States, Germany,
France, Portugal, Hong Kong and Taiwan have established operations
in Macao, their combined assets reaching more than 50 billion
patacas. Macao's highly internationalized financial industry has
become one of the four pillars of the local economy. An official
from the local branch of a French Bank said that Macao will serve
as an effective channel for banking business that is oriented for
the China market.
</P>
<P>
And nothing could have linked Macao more closely with the world
economy than its gaming and tourism industry. Last year, Macao
received more than 6.94 million visitors from outside the region,
17 times the local population. In the ten months of this year, in
the run-up to Macao's return to China on December 20, more than 6.
1 million tourists from around the world thronged to Macao, up 6.2
percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
