<HEADLINE> Feature: Macao-Born Portuguese: Macao, Our Home (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The emblem of Associacao dos
Macaenses (Association of Macao-Born Portuguese) is unique and eye-
catching with designs of "Guia Lighthouse", built by Portuguese in
1865, "A-Ma Temple", a typical Chinese architecture built over 500
years ago, and the Map of Macao.
</P>
<P>
"Macanese" is a Portuguese expression for Macao-born Portuguese
or Macao-born mixed-blood of Portuguese and Chinese or of
Portuguese and other Asian ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
The emblem reflects the special ties between Macao-born
Portuguese and Macao and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
"The majority of us will not leave Macao," said Dr. Luiz F.D.S.
Pedruco, president of the association, "because Macao has long
been our home."
</P>
<P>
On December 13, one week before the founding of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (MSAR) of the People's Republic of
China (PRC), this three-year-old association finally has its own
office in a downtown apartment. "It demonstrates that we have
taken root here," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"One who is planning to move somewhere will never bother to
find a new house," explained the Macao-born Portuguese who speaks
both fluent Portuguese and Cantonese. "However, after the handover,
all of us should learn to speak Putonghua (Chinese Mandarin)," he
said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that there are more than 10,000 Macao-
born Portuguese or mix-blood among Macao's 430,000 population.
They are a unique part of Macao people who are raised in two
different cultures since their childhood.
</P>
<P>
Macao-born Portuguese and the mix-blood who better understand
Chinese and European cultures can play their due role in the Sino-
Portuguese relations or Sino-Western relations, he noted.
</P>
<P>
There has been concerns about whether Macao-born Portuguese are
going to leave after China resumes its exercise of sovereignty
over the region on December 20.
</P>
<P>
Facts speak louder than words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Macao-Born Portuguese: Macao, Our Home (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rita Botelho Dos Santos, Estefania's aunt who patronized her
niece for university study, said, "I will be very happy to see
that our younger generation could live well in Macao." Being a
senior government official, Rita is now busy learning songs to be
sung at the handover celebrations.
</P>
<P>
"It is absolutely a right decision for us to stay," said Rita,
noting that according to the basic law of the MSAR, the rights and
interests of Macao-born Portuguese and the mix-blood as well as
their customs and culture will be respected and protected and
those who work with the government can keep their jobs.
</P>
<P>
With the Basic Law and the Central Government's thoughtfulness,
the majority of the Macao-born Portuguese are no longer worried
about their future after the handover. As a matter of fact, some
Macao-born Portuguese who have left are thinking of coming back,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Macao-born Portuguese have served as a bridge linking the Macao
Government with the Macao people, they will surely play a special
role in China's relations with Portugal and Europe after Macao's
return to the motherland, she noted.
</P>
<P>
Just as the out-going Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira puts it
Macao-born Portuguese are "indispensable" for Macao.
</P>
<P>
These days, 200 Macao-born Portuguese are practicing Portuguese
folk dance as part of their celebrations for the handover.
</P>
<P>
"These dancers can represent all the Macao-born Portuguese.
Since we have been part of this great family of Macao, we don't
want to be onlookers in the celebration activities," said Jose
Maria Pereia Coutinho, an official with the Economic Services of
the Macao Government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
