<HEADLINE> COMESA to Meet in Egypt Over Free Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) is to hold its first ever regional
economic conference in Cairo, Egypt in February 2000, Zambia Daily
Mail newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Making the announcement at a presentation attended by COMESA
Secretary General Erastus Mwencha in Lusaka on Wednesday, Egyptian
Ambassador to Zambia Reda Bebars said the conference under the
theme "COMESA 2000: the Emerging Market" aims to increase
awareness of the international business community on COMESA as an
emerging economic bloc that has a stable predictable trade and
investment regime.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which is also aimed at attracting both domestic
and foreign investment, is expected to contribute toward the
realization of the COMESA Free Trade Area due to start on October
31, 2000, Bebars said.
</P>
<P>
"It will contribute to the identification and promotion of
investment opportunities in the COMESA region as well as enhance
intra-COMESA trade and economic relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, an Egyptian delegation led by Bebars
is currently in Zambia making consultations with the Zambian
government and the COMESA secretariat on the conference to be held
on February 28 and 29 in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
According to Egypt's International Economic Forum Manager Nakia
Lamboum, the conference would attract over 1,000 delegates,
including COMESA member state ministers, regional company
representatives and representatives of international co-operating
partners. 
</P>
