<HEADLINE> Uganda's Key Rebel Leaders to Be Relocated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Eight of the 24 key commanders
of the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA), a key rebel group reportedly
fighting the Ugandan government from southern Sudan, will be
relocated later this month from Sudan to countries of their
choices.
</P>
<P>
This will be conducted under the agreement reached between
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and his Sudanese counterpart
Omar al-Bashir in Kenya's capital Nairobi on December 8,
Thursday's New Vision daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Those to be relocated include LRA's top commander Joseph Kony
and other high-ranking officers. They have reportedly been
separated from their fighters and captives in camps south of Juba
city in southern Sudan, the report said.
</P>
<P>
At least 200 captives in Sudan, many of them girls, will be the
first batch to be brought back to Uganda, the report said, adding
the return work will be arranged in phases.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the two presidents have also agreed not to
harbor, sponsor or give military or logistical support to any
rebel groups, opposition groups or hostile elements from each
other's territories.
</P>
<P>
They resolved to disband and disarm terrorist groups and to
prevent any acts of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Some of the LRA rebels who have surrendered to the government
will either be absorbed into the government army or sent to
schools, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The LRA rebels have been fighting the Ugandan government since
the ruling National Resistance Movement came to power in 1986.
More than 10,000 people have been abducted since then.
</P>
<P>
Besides the bilateral agreement reached between Uganda and
Sudan, Uganda Parliament passed a long-awaited Amnesty Bill on
December 7, granting blanket amnesty to rebels who have been
fighting to topple Museveni's government since 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
