<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya on Track to Economic Recovery: Senior </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has been back on track
toward its economic recovery in the last four months, Kenya's top
civil servant has said.
</P>
<P>
The international Monetary Fund (IMF) could reopen talks with
Kenya next month and after that "a major announcement" would be
made, the Kenya Times daily Thursday quoted Head of Civil Service
Richard Leakey as saying here.
</P>
<P>
Leakey expressed his optimism Wednesday about the resumption of
the 205 million U.S. dollars loan halted in July 1997 by the IMF
in protest against Kenya's poor governance, which has triggered an
economic downturn in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Leaky was named as the country's top public servant in July
this year by President Daniel arap Moi as part of the economic
recovery strategy, which also ushered other technocrats into the
government.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the recovery strategy is progressing well
with the achievements in curbing corruption and improving
efficiency in the government, Leaky said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the government will continue its commitment
to streamlining civil service and fighting corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
