<HEADLINE> EU Ban of Ugandan Fish to Stay for Half Year: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) ban on
 importation of Ugandan fish and fish products, initiated in April
this year, would stay for another half year unless the
international standards required by the EU are met, a senior U.N.
official has said.
</P>
<P>
The fish products in Uganda still have some deficiencies, an
official with the United Nations Industry, Development
Organization was quoted by Thursday's New Vision newspaper as
saying at a workshop.
</P>
<P>
Fish export has been the third largest foreign exchange earner
for Uganda after coffee and tourism. The EU is Uganda's biggest
fish market and its ban has made Uganda lose nearly one million
U.S. dollars each week.
</P>
<P>
Two teams from the European bloc have come to Uganda to inspect
the fishing and landing sites since the ban began, to the
conclusion that their sanitation standards are not met. 
</P>
