<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Snoring in Pregnancy Poses Risk to Baby: Researchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Snoring in pregnancy may
indicate the mother's blood pressure is up and the baby at risk,
AAP said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A study at Sydney's Royal Prince Alfred Hospital (RPAH) sleep
unit showed women with interrupted breathing due to snoring had
raised blood pressure at night, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
High blood pressure could massively constrict blood flow from
the placenta to the baby, and put the mother at risk of stroke or
heart attack, it said.
</P>
<P>
AAP quoted Research Fellow Dr. Natalie Edwards as saying a
fetus deprived of oxygen because the mother's breathing stops -
known as sleep apnoea - may have retarded growth.
</P>
<P>
"In our study we found women were snoring and although not
having apnoea, there was air flow limitation," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Their oxygen doesn't go down but their carbon dioxide
increases a little bit, and we think that is what is causing their
blood pressure to go up during the night," she said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Edwards said partners should alert pregnant women to bad
snoring.
</P>
<P>
The study, due to be published in the American Journal of
Respiratory and Critical Care Medicine, has already sparked
international interest, with offers of collaborative research
coming from France and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
