<HEADLINE> Kenya's Power Rationing to Last Until Next June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The power rationing since
September in Kenya may last until next June due to shortages of
water at hydro-power stations, Kenya Power and Lighting Company
has predicted.
</P>
<P>
With the current short rain season fading, the rising of water
levels in power plants has become unlikely, the company's Managing
Director Samuel Gichuru was quoted by Thursday's East African
Standard as saying.
</P>
<P>
The short rains appeared to have come to an end by
mid-December, the only option is to wait for the start of the long
rains in March or early April, Gichuru said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Kenyan Energy Minister Francis Masakhalia
ruled out the possibility of importing an emergency electricity
generator to ease the rationing, citing that it is too expensive
and would affect Kenya's financial situation negatively.
</P>
<P>
The power rationing in the east African country has badly
disrupted the industrial sector and caused inconvenience in the
daily life of the residents. It is also discouraging the potential
inflow of foreign investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
