<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stanford Experts: Cox Committee Conclusions "Unwarranted" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Five experts from Stanford
University Wednesday said in a critique that the congressional
report on alleged Chinese espionage contained "inflammatory"
language, "unwarranted" conclusions and tarred all Chinese
visitors to the United States as potential spies.
</P>
<P>
The 99-page critique, edited by Michael M. May, of the Stanford
Center for International Security and Cooperation, charges that
the report of the special congressional committee headed by Rep.
Christopher Cox, R-Newport Beach, failed to back up what it calls
"a number of spectacular accusations" against China and several U.
S. research facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Cox committee had charged that for two decades China was
engaged in "aggressive espionage" and exploited lax U.S. security
to steal classified information on the most advanced U.S. nuclear
weapons to improve its own missile technology targeting U.S.
cities.
</P>
<P>
"Some important and relevant facts are wrong and a number of
conclusions are, in our view, unwarranted," May wrote in the
introduction of the critique.
</P>
<P>
May said there's a conflict between "the two presumed purposes
of the Cox report." On one hand, the report tries to portray China
as technologically backward, to explain why it would need to steal
U.S. nuclear secrets. On the other hand, it stresses the imminent
threat to the United States by making China appear to be a world
power with a modern nuclear capability.
</P>
<P>
"They (Cox Committee) are getting only half the story," said
Marco DiCapua, a former counselor for science and technology
affairs at the U.S. Embassy in Beijing. "Our report is a companion.
They both should be on the shelves of policy-makers and decision
makers and scholars, side by side."
</P>
<P>
The other three experts who are involved in the critique are
Alastair Iain Johnston, a Harvard professor who is a visiting
scholar at Stanford; Wolfgang K. H. Panofsky, former director of
the Stanford High Energy Physics Laboratory; and Lewis R. Franklin,
a career intelligence expert on Chinese and Russian missile and
space research.
</P>
<P>
The Stanford authors also point to numerous factual errors in
the Cox report.
</P>
<P>
For example, the report seems to confuse kilometers for miles
in giving the range of China's JL-2 ballistic missile -- saying
the range is 7,500 miles, when in fact it is 7,800 kilometers, or
approximately 4,871 miles. The difference is crucial because the
extra range would mean the missile could target all of the United
States, as the Cox report claims, rather than only parts of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The critique also takes the Cox committee to task for often
citing allegations as fact.
</P>
<P>
"They make the blanket accusation that the Chinese have stolen
information on the entire U.S. nuclear stockpile, but they present
no evidence of it," said Wolfgang K.H. Panofsky, one of the
authors and director emeritus of the Stanford Linear Accelerator
Center. Panofsky has been one of the most outspoken critics of the
Cox committee report.
</P>
<P>
The Stanford physicist writes that the Cox report fails to
present evidence that the nuclear design information supposedly
gained through Chinese espionage could have been obtained from
public sources or developed by the Chinese on their own without
the aid of U.S. information
</P>
<P>
The Cox report followed allegations that nuclear physicist Wen
Ho Lee illegally downloaded a vast quantity of secret data from
computers at Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico. The
charges cast a spotlight on alleged security lapses at U.S.
weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
The Stanford experts said the Cox report alleged that
essentially all Chinese visitors to the United States are
potential spies. "This has cast a cloud of suspicion over both
foreign and Asian-born U.S. staff members of U.S. companies."
</P>
<P>
The Stanford report, available on the World Wide Web (www.
stanford.edu/group/CISAC), said the experts felt the Cox Committee
report made a number of "spectacular" accusations against China
and its language, particularly in its overview, was "inflammatory.
"
</P>
<P>
"I think it got some things out of proportion that were quite
important to get straight. Without some perspective it could lead
to bad effects," May said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
