<HEADLINE> Zambia Urged to Declare Orphan Crisis a Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has been asked to immediately declare the crisis facing
orphans and other vulnerable children in the country as a national
disaster, Zambia's "The Post" newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released by the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) on Wednesday, this was a key
recommendation from a three-day national planning workshop for
orphans and other vulnerable children held here last week.
</P>
<P>
"The 200 delegates unanimously approved the workshop's
resolution which proposed that the disaster mitigation and
management unit in the office of the vice-president should develop
an appropriate response to the disaster, in collaboration with
other ministers and organs of civil society," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The delegates recommended that structures be urgently mobilized
at all levels from grass-roots to the government and that workable
mechanism be urgently established to facilitate communication,
co-ordination and access to resources among all actors dealing
with orphans and vulnerable children, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also discussed issues affecting children such as
education, health services, psycho-social distress, HIV/AIDS and
children's life on the streets. 
</P>
