<HEADLINE> Panamanian Vessel Sinks In South China Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A cargo ship from Panama sank
in the South China Sea at 10:10 am (Beijing Time) today, but the
crew of 17 sailors have all been rescued, according to the China
Maritime Search and Rescue Center.
</P>
<P>
The 3000-ton vessel, named "Violet Ocean," was enroute from
Papua New Guinea to Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong
province, carrying 3000 tons of logs, said Zhai Jiugang, an
official with the China Maritime Security Administration(CMSA).
</P>
<P>
It encountered strong gales and high waves at 1:50 am (Beijing
Time) at a spot 40 nautical miles southeast of Shantou, another
port of Guangdong province, and began to sink.
</P>
<P>
The CMSA sent rescuers immediately after receiving a distress
call from the ship. Ships and a naval frigate were dispatched to
the scene, and CMSA also ordered the local coastal radio station
to maintain contact with the vessel as well as to inform fishing
boats nearby to give a hand.
</P>
<P>
"Allowing for the possibility that the logs on board would
probably separate from the ship and affect the local navigation
after the ship sank, we also warned ships nearby to remain on the
alert," Zhai said.
</P>
<P>
At 8:45 am this morning, the "Yin Xing" ship of the China
Shipping Group, which first reached the spot, succeeded in saving
the 17 South Korean sailors after nearly five hours.
</P>
<P>
Zhai said that the cause of the accident is still under
investigation, but he speculated that the rocky sea conditions
caused the ship to sink.  
</P>
</TEXT>
