<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke121618 - Roundup: Bangladesh Experiences Continued Political Confrontation in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh witnessed continued
political confrontation in the year 1999, with the opposition so
far having called 18 countrywide hartals (destructive strikes),
demanding immediate resignation of the government and snap
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP), the Jatiya Party, the
Jamaat-e-Islami and the Islami Oikya Jote (Islamic Solidarity
Front) - four opposition parties which are all represented in the
parliament - formed an anti-government alliance early this year,
in an effort to intensify their oust-government movement.
</P>
<P>
The alliance first boycotted municipal elections in late
February by staging nationwide shutdowns to press home their four-
point demands which included the resignation of the chief election
commissioner, reorganization of the Election Commission, issuance
of voters' identity cards before the elections and release of all
political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties said they would not take part in any
elections under the present chief election commissioner, and vowed
to resist any polls thereafter without the participation of the
opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
"We will not take part in any election under the incumbent
chief election commissioner and we seek parliamentary elections
first under a caretaker administration," BNP Secretary General
Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan once told a leading weekly newspaper here.
</P>
<P>
The opposition also went on an unofficial boycott of parliament
this year, on such pretexts as to protest the government's
decision in late July to examine the proposal of providing road
transshipment facilities to India, the government's unilateral
decision to hold city corporation polls, and opposition law-makers
being deprived the right time to speak in parliament.
</P>
<P>
In the opposition camp, the Jatiya Party, the third largest
party in the country, experienced a split early this year when
party chief H.M. Ershad withdrew support to the Awami League (AL)-
led "government of national consensus" and joined forces with
other opposition parties to oppose the government while his party
general secretary refused to quit as a cabinet minister.
</P>
<P>
And the AL also encountered a crisis when party leader Abdul
Siddiqui staged a rebellion against the leadership of AL President
Sheik Hasina, who is also the incumbent prime minister, by making
public speeches and statements criticizing the government and
demanding an account of the assets and property of the prime
minister, her relatives and the cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
Siddiqui, who was consequently expelled in late July from the
party on charges of breaking party discipline and indulging in
anti-organizational activities, has hinted that he would float a
new party within this month which might include some ruling party
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Evidence showed that Siddiqui would probably join the anti-
government movement of the opposition alliance sooner or later,
political analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
The climax of the anti-government movement came in late
November when chiefs of the four parties of the opposition
alliance sat together, the first summit of the nearly-one-year
alliance, vowing to oust the government and forming a patriotic
and strong government on a "broad-based unity."
</P>
<P>
The analysts said the summit and its declaration showed that
the four parties have finally agreed on a same platform in their
joint movement to oust the government, and that the four parties
must have reached consensus on how to contest the next
parliamentary elections, jointly or separately and how to share
power if their movement is successful.
</P>
<P>
Many people had hoped that the anti-government movement would
come into a recess during the month of Ramadan beginning December
10 after a countrywide strike early this month following the much-
talked-about summit.
</P>
<P>
The hope was smashed, however, when the Election Commission's
announcement on December 7 of polls to the city corporation in
Chittagong, southeast Bangladesh, early next month and the
opposition's subsequent nationwide shutdown on December 13 and a
two-day strike in the seaport city on December 13-14.
</P>
<P>
Hasina repeatedly urged to opposition to "shun the path of
hartal" and "come to dialog" this year, a proposal the
opposition has rejected, arguing that the ruling party was not
sincere as the AL even did not bother to make it written and
formal.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of reconciliation between the ruling and the
opposition parties was very thin for the time being considering
the political atmosphere in the country, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
They added that the political situation in the South Asian
nation is most likely to remain uncertain next year, but one thing
is certain: the opposition alliance will organize more programs,
such as strikes and rallies, to unseat the three-and-half-year-old
government and to prepare for the next general elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
