<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: HK, Macao Hand In Hand Into New Millenium (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The trade and economic relationship between Hong Kong and Macao
will be enhanced after the change of sovereignty, he said, adding
that there are good prospects for economic development in the
south China region.
</P>
<P>
"No doubt both Hong Kong and Macao will make good use of these
economic opportunities," Tsang concluded.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Justice Elsie Leung said that in the past two and
half years, the legal system of Hong Kong has been tested by winds
and rain, but it has made headway.
</P>
<P>
"On the whole, the experience makes me more confident about the
success of 'One Country, Two Systems'", she said, adding that it
has demonstrated the wisdom of the Chinese in resolving problems
left over by history.
</P>
<P>
After the return, Hong Kong has a constitutional order, but it
has also preserved the previous common law system, she said,
adding that it forms the skeleton of Hong Kong's legal system.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the common law, rules of equity, ordinances
and customary law form the fabric of this legal system and they
are not in conflict with each other, she added. "In fact they
certainly can mix together well," she noted.
</P>
<P>
Leung said that through actual practice over the past two years
and more, the great concept of "One Country, Two Systems" has been
realized in Hong Kong. "And I firmly believe that this concept can
likewise be implemented in Macao," Leung stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
