<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Australia Seen Shifting its Regional Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- At the end of the 20th
century, Australia is witnessed a significant policy shift by
waving away its 25-year regional strategy to drift from Asia.
</P>
<P>
During the 1998s when the Asian economies were going up, the
former Australian governments decided to merge Australia into Asia.
They pursued the target with active diplomatic measures. The
country took an active part in the Cambodian peace process and
proposed to set up the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation Forum
APED and held a goodwill stance toward the closest and strongest
neighbor Indonesia and signed a bilateral security treaty with
Indonesia in 1995.
</P>
<P>
At home, the then Hawke and Keating governments started a great
project to produce a multicultural community to water down its
white color. Meanwhile they opened the door to Asian immigrants
and paid more attention to the Asian culture.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, however, all these have been derided and abandoned by
the Howard government. Prime Minister John Howard said the Keating
government was like a beggar boy with his nose pressed at the
window of the rich man's club of Asia and was not aware Australia
itself was something the Asian countries were eager to enter into.
</P>
<P>
It has been noticed that Prime Minister John Howard rarely
brings the word of "multiculture" up to his lips. His government
handles Asian illegal immigrants in such a way as if it were faced
with a disaster. Arrival of every boat of illegal Asian immigrants
would touch off a series of outcries, saying the country was
getting submerged by the Asian immigrant flood.
</P>
<P>
However, official statistics show that the first biggest part
of the illegal immigrants into Australia come by air from Britain
and the second biggest part from the United States. But nobody has
ever mentioned them nor has the government sent them to detainment
centers, merely because they are white and do not threaten
Australia's white characteristic.
</P>
<P>
The country's European characteristic is a topic stressed
repeatedly by Prime Minister John Howard. His latest mention of it
was on September 17 when he said that "we're the only nation that
really brings to Asia that combination of European history and
heritage, American association and Asian geography."
</P>
<P>
He sees the link with the motherland Britain as valuable as his
life, and desperately struggled against a republic choice in the
November referendum because a republic means cessation of the
critical links with Britain. In order to spotlight the European
background, Howard will head a big group of politicians to London
next July to have an audience with the Queen and celebrate the
Australian Federation's centenary.
</P>
<P>
Behind the policy change there has been a wind change. After
the Cold War, the West has taken a more aggressive attitude in
exporting and imposing its value and system. In the region, the
South-East Asian countries have been stricken by an economic
crisis since 1997 while the Australian economy is expanding
steadily into its 9th successive year. The daily Age claimed on
October 20 that "the economies of Australia and New Zealand have
to be taken seriously in the region, because their combined gross
domestic product is about the same as that of all the South-East
Asian economies together."
</P>
<P>
Sixteen years ago, the then Australian Prime Minister Bob Hawke
said that "our own future is now more dependent on our neighboring
countries than they will be on us." But now many Australians
believe the situation got reversed and Asian countries need
Australia more than the latter needs them.
</P>
<P>
There is an increasing evidence that Australians are turning
away from Asia. For instance, the number of young people enrolling
in Asian studies courses are declining. Books on Asian subjects
are harder to publish and sell less well.
</P>
<P>
It was against this background that Howard Doctrine was
fermented. The core of the doctrine has been reported as
increasing military expenditure to act "in a sort of deputy
peacekeeping capacity in our region to the global policeman role
in the United States." Faced with sharp criticism from neighboring
countries, Howard denied he had used the word "deputy." Then, the
new policy was described as "phantom doctrine."
</P>
<P>
The doctrine was finally repudiated while the phantom keeps
clouding over the hearts and minds of the South-East Asian nations,
especially Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
On November 15 this year, authorized by the United Nations,
Australia led a multi-national troop into East Timor. Talking
about this, Prime Minister Howard announced officially that "we're
not big enough to be a policeman anywhere but we are big enough
and economically strong enough to play a constructive, positive
leadership role in an area like this and on an issue such as this.
"
</P>
<P>
Now the problem is whether the South-East Asian countries
welcome a leader from the West. So far, they are highly sensitive
on their sovereignty and have long stuck to a non-interventionist
policy in each other's affairs even within themselves. To any
Western motives, they are keeping more vigilance especially after
the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's Deputy Prime Minister Abdullay Badawi reportedly
declared in November that "We did not appoint them (Australians).
We don't wish to see any nation which sees itself as keeper or
leader or commander in the region."
</P>
<P>
Indonesia turned its back on Australia. The relationship
between the two reached its lowest point since 1960s. On November
16 this year, the next day that the Australian-led multinational
troop poured into East Timor, Indonesia canceled the bilateral
security treaty signed with Australia in 1995. Recently,
Indonesian new President Abdurrahman Wahid said he did not care if
the relationship would worsen.
</P>
<P>
Australia wants to lead the region but the Asian countries
refuse any leadership from the West. It is a contradiction that
will lead the political ties of Australia with its neighbors into
a new round of convulsions of fear and distrust, though economic
cooperation between them seems to be continuing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Holds Millennium Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A Myanmar millennium conference,
sponsored by the country's Universities Historical Research
Department, is being held here and is participated by Myanmar and
international scholars.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day conference, which began on Wednesday, the
scholars will exchange views and hold discussions on cultural
heritage of Myanmar history and traditions and culture, lessons to
learn and challenges of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the conference, Myanmar
Minister of Education U Than Aung said fossils of human beings
were recently found in Pondaung and Ponnya regions, the country's
Sagaing division, calling for continuation of the work to recover
the valuable records of the past.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the new means to be found by the Myanmar and
international scholars at the paper reading session of the
conference will help solve the problems and overcome the
challenges of the new century.
</P>
<P>
Scholars from Australia, Britain, Bangladesh, China, France,
Germany, India, Japan, Myanmar, Singapore, the United States,
Thailand and Vietnam are scheduled to read 44 papers at the
conference including that on Myanmar's past 2,000 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
