<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Likely to Face Prolonged, Cold Winter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is likely to
experience severe and prolonged cold during this winter, The
Bangladesh Observer reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Weather experts in Dhaka were quoted as predicting that the
biting cold wind would begin sweeping the northern region of the
country by early next week, and dense fog may cover up many of the
coastal areas of the country with the approach of the jet wind.
</P>
<P>
The entire country will gradually come under the intensive grip
of the cold wind within late December, and the wind is likely to
become more intensified from the first week of January that may
continue until mid-February.
</P>
<P>
Officials predicted that the country may experience record-low
temperature this year because of unusual dry atmosphere coupled
with extremely poor presence of moisture in the soil, caused from
abrupt fall of sub-soil water level in different regions of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The intensity of cold was remarkably less during the last
winter because of what scientists said availability of more than
enough moisture in the soil that came from the devastating flood
last year.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Director of the Meteorological Office Mohammad Akram
Hossain said the winter this year had arrived a little behind the
schedule due to unusual presence of "easterly warm wave." 
</P>
</TEXT>
