<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, December 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Rome-based FAO said in a report reaching here that most of
the worst affected countries, including Angola, Burundi, Sierra
Leone, Somalia and Sudan, are suffering from recent or ongoing
civil conflicts. (FAO-Africa)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TUCSON -- The U.S. and African energy ministers Wednesday
afternoon issued the Tucson Communique here, saying that they
vowed to strengthen energy cooperation among and between the
United States and African countries.
</P>
<P>
The communique came at the end of the three-day U.S.-African
Energy Ministers Conference, which, beginning here Monday, was the
first international event that has gathered the U.S. energy
minister, Bill Richardson, and some 50 of his African counterparts
in this sun-shining city. (US-Africa)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Commerce Department said Wednesday that
the country's stockpiles of goods on shelves and backlots
increased by 0.2 percent in October, pushing total business
inventories to 1.26 trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Though marking the slowest growth in business inventories since
April, October's gain was the ninth straight monthly increase this
year. In September, total business inventories rose by 0.4
percent, the fastest pace in six months. (US-Business Inventories)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- The U.S. economic growth that began nearly nine
years ago will continue in 2000, though at a slower pace than in
the past several years, a report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report from the Bond Market Association said that its
Economic Advisory Committee, which is composed of noted economists
from securities firms and banks, also expects additional
tightening by the Federal Reserve during 2000, probably in March,
resulting in somewhat higher interest rates. The unemployment
rate is expected to hold at or below 1999 level through 2000, but
without any rise in inflation.  (US-Economy)
</P>
