<HEADLINE> Thai Officials Banned from Traveling in Censure Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Thai Interior Ministry high-
ranking officials have been banned from traveling, both locally
and abroad, during the parliamentary censure debate, The Nation
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Provincial governors, deputies and assistant provincial
governors have also been ordered to stay within their jurisdiction
and monitor the no-confidence debate. They must immediately
forward necessary information to the ministry if issues occurred
in their jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry has also set up special centers in all
76 provinces, which have officials stationed to monitor the debate,
gather and send relevant information to the ministry's computer
center in parliament.
</P>
<P>
The travel ban is also applied for ranking police officers.
Police commissioner general Pracha Promnok ordered police from the
rank of commander across the country to closely follow the debate
and provide necessary information online to parliament.
</P>
<P>
Finance Ministry officials are also on standby to gather
information online from the bad-loan laden state-owned Krung Thai
Bank, the Bank of Thailand and the Securities Exchange Commission.
Officials of the Defense Ministry was ordered to be on alert and
fully prepared to assist Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai in retorting
accusations raised by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry, Interior Ministry and Defense Ministry
are the three major ministries targeted in the debate, which
opened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is the third censure debate against the Democrat-led
coalition, but its 236-149 majority in parliament is expected to
help it survive a no-confidence vote at the end of the three-day
debate.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the opposition's goal is to damage the Democrats
as much as possible ahead of new elections Chuan must call by
November 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
