<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Twelve ultra-leftist
guerrilla members were killed Wednesday in encounters with police
in Rukum and Rolpa district in mid-western Nepal, the Kathmandu
Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to Rajendra Bahadur Singh, deputy inspector general
of police of the Mid-western Regional Police Office, police
discovered two guerrilla camps in the middle of a jungle and a
cross fire took place consequently.
</P>
<P>
Twelve guerrilla members were killed, including two women. No
police casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
Police seized one rifle, one shot-gun, some pipe bombs, hand
bombs, fuse wire, detonator and utensils enough for 50 people.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 people, including police, guerrilla members and
civilians, have been killed since 1996. 
