<HEADLINE> South Korean Bank Gives Loan for Reactor Construction in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Export-Import Bank of Korea
has agreed to supply a loan of 3.22 billion U.S. dollars to the
Korea Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO) for the
construction of light-water reactors in the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), the bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the loan will be earmarked for the
construction of two light-water nuclear reactors, which the United
States, South Korea and Japan have agreed on to ease tensions on
the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be extended on an interest-free basis, while the
principal should be repaid in six-month installments over 20 years,
including a three-year grace period, after the completion of two
reactors, said the bank.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the DPRK signed an agreement in Geneva in
October 1994 to build the reactors in return for Pyongyang's
abandonment of its alleged nuclear development.
</P>
<P>
The two light-water reactors with a capacity of 1,000 megawatts
each will be built in Kumho, an eastern coastal area of the DPRK's
Hamyong Province, at a cost of 4.6 billion U.S. dollars, of which
South Korea will provide 3.22 billion U.S. dollars, Japan one
billion and the United States the rest.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Electric Power Corp. will construct the
reactors and install and manage fundamental facilities while the
KEDO will be responsible for supplying a work site, communication
facilities and securing workers' safety. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
