<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania's Largest Opposition: Solve Government Crisis Legally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Romania's largest opposition
party Wednesday repeated its appeal for a legal solution to the
current government crisis caused Tuesday by President Emil
Constantinescu's order to remove Prime Minister Radu Vasile.
</P>
<P>
Ion Iliescu, chairman of the Romanian Social Democracy Party,
stressed in the appeal that the country's law gives only the
parliament, not the president, the authority to sack the prime
minister, and therefore urged the president and the ruling
coalition to "correct their error."
</P>
<P>
He told the press that the crisis can be resolved properly only
by a parliamentary vote of no-confidence on the government given
Vasile's refusal to resign. But first of all, the president should
retract his order, which is unconstitutional, he demanded.
</P>
<P>
Before all these done, he added, his party will not consider
talking with the president about any issue including a possible
new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
President Constantinescu's order has already provoked strong
reaction across the country. Most of Romania's opposition groups
and law experts have questioned its legality, though some others
hold it a pressing priority now to end the crisis and form a new
cabinet as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Vasile's dismissal was ordered early Tuesday after he refused
to resign even after the ruling Christian Democratic National
Peasant's Party and its major coalition partners withdrew their
support, and 10 cabinet ministers announced quitting in a bid to
force him out.
</P>
<P>
Vasile rejected the order, which he said is "unconstitutional,"
and later the same day, expressed the intention to remain a
senator without mentioning resignation.
</P>
<P>
President Constantinescu and the ruling coalition groups met on
Wednesday night to choose a new prime minister. As they are widely
apart on the candidates, it appears unlikely that either Interior
Minister Constantin Dudu Ionescu or the head of the state property
fund Radu Sarbu would succeed Vasile as previously expected.
</P>
<P>
At present, Mugur Isarescu, an independent and chief of the
Romanian State Bank, has seemed the most likely choice acceptable
to all.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
