<HEADLINE> South Korean Army to Change Signaling Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Army will
obtain 34 advanced signaling devices next year to replace old ones,
said the Defense Ministry on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new radio sets, made by South Korean Daeyoung Electronics,
are among the 1,378 sets of signal equipment worth about 570
billion won (some 470 million U.S. dollars) that the Army plans to
procure within the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The 34 VHF sets of radios are modeled after Canada's AN/GRC-512,
which the ministry selected in May this year over a Swedish model.
</P>
<P>
LG Precision, teamed with the Swedish company which failed to
win the Defense Ministry's bid, has sent letters of complaint to
the government, claiming that Swedish Ericsson's RL-402A model was
superior to the Canadian Marconi model.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry responded that both models have similar
capabilities and there is no problem with its selection of the
Canadian model in terms of price and capability.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian model is some four million won (some 3,300 dollars)
cheaper than the Swedish one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
