<HEADLINE> New Bridge Opened in Myanmar's Rakhine State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A new bridge built on the
Yangon-Sittway highway in Myanmar's western Rakhine state was
commissioned for service Wednesday, official newspaper The New
Light of Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 390-meter-long Ramong bridge in the state's Minbye township
was built at a cost of 2.3 million U.S. dollars plus 1.584 billion
Kyats (5.28 million dollars), it said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inaugural ceremony of the bridge, Lieutenant-
General Khin Nyunt, first secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and
Development Council, disclosed that over 800 small and 10 major
bridges were built on the highway alone in the state which is a
coastal area criss-crossed by rivers and streams.
</P>
<P>
Three more bridges in the state are under construction and will
soon be completed, he said.
</P>
<P>
By the time when all the bridges on the highway are completed,
people from Sittway can travel to Yangon directly by road and to
all parts of the Myanmar through a mountain pass, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that a deep sea-port will also be built in
the state where sea fishing, fish and prawn breeding and marine
enterprises are flourishing, saying that prospects will be bright
by having this sea port to extend foreign trade and to enhance
tourism in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar has built 114 bridges
including 12 major ones and 5,871 km of roads since 1988. The
total length of roads has been extended to 29,187 km in 1999 from
23,316 km in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
