<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Listed Among World Top Ten Air Carriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The sector of civil aviation in
China has been expanding at a pace twice the growth rate for
national economy since 1980, making China one of the world's top
ten air carriers.
</P>
<P>
This was told at an international conference on reform of China
's basis economies held recently in Haikou, capital of the island
province of Hainan in south China.
</P>
<P>
By 1998, the sector had transported a total of 57.55 million
passengers and 1.4 million tons of cargoes, a rise of 16.5 percent
and 15.7 percent respectively on 1980 figures.
</P>
<P>
Air traffic has now become a vital means of transport in China.
</P>
<P>
China's civil aviation industry has now launched 1,122 air
routes, 983 of which are domestic lines, and built an air traffic
network linking 199 cities worldwide, including 64 cities in 34
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
By 1998, enterprises of the civil aviation industry in China
had registered a total of 183.44 billion yuan of assets, 80 times
the figure for 1978, the year when China introduced the reform and
opening-up policy.
</P>
<P>
At present, the industry now boasts a fleet of some 800
passenger planes, as against 50 small-sized planes in early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
There are now 143 airports available for passenger planes
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Those speedy growth are resultant from a reform to encourage
the use of local and overseas investment in the aviation industry.
</P>
<P>
During the 20-year period from 1978 to 1998, local governments'
spending on airport construction amounted to 42.9 billion yuan,
with the use of overseas loans reaching 1.23 billion US dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anhui Seeking For Int'l Effort To Save Wetlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province is
working to seek international cooperation for protecting local
wetland resources, which are shrinking in size and deteriorating,
a threat posed by varied human factors.
</P>
<P>
The Huaihe River and the Yangtze, the longest in China, flow
through Anhui province, helping form 3.8 million ha of wetlands
locally, which accounts 27.8 percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
This means that Anhui boasts the largest area of wetlands in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands have comprehensive strong points, such as nurturing
water sources, storing floodwater, regulating climate, as well as
disposing of sewage, along with provision of a haven for wildlife,
especially endangered water fowls.
</P>
<P>
The increasing population living in valleys of the Yangtze and
Huaihe rivers in recent years, has accelerated the decrease and
worsening of the wetlands, where a renowned home for rare and
precious wildlife and plants like Chinese alligator, white dolphin,
red-crowned crane, diatom and hornwort.
</P>
<P>
Though Anhui has begun to set up nature reserves for wetlands
since 1982, it currently has only brought 4.6 percent of local
wetlands under protection, because of technology and fund
shortages.
</P>
<P>
The province intends to introduce overseas technology,
facilities and money to do such research works on wetlands
environment, waterfowl resources, and migratory birds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
