<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Press Confident in Freedom of Speech After Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- "Macao Forum" is a popular
hotline program at the local broadcasting station in Macao, at
which the audience may freely discuss political, economic and
social problems or even criticize the government with no need to
identify themselves.
</P>
<P>
A special focus for the program on Dec. 19 is to invite the
audience to voice their opinions on Macao's return to China and
their expectations for the government of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
"This is a hot topic of the Macao people today, and we hope the
audience may participate in the program and show their concerns
about Macao's future," said U Kin Tong, chief editor of the news
department at the Macao Radio Station.
</P>
<P>
"The special program also speaks out our common hope for the
SAR government to respect the freedom of press and allow such
programs as Macao Forum to continue," he said.
</P>
<P>
Macao, a peninsula at the mouth of the Pearl River Delta in
south China, is to return to China on Dec. 20 after being ruled by
the Portuguese for more than 150 years.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the relatively complete press law system in
Macao, there won't be a big problem in freedom of press, U Kin
Tong said.
</P>
<P>
Macao people are free to run newspapers and news agencies on
their own without government censorship, and all they need to
abide by is some rules such as the ban for personal attacks and
libel.
</P>
<P>
The Macao SAR Basic Law also says that all Macao residents are
entitled to enjoy freedom of speech, press and publication.
</P>
<P>
The main criterion for judging news value will continue to be
the degree of public concern for the events, so as to provide a
good variety of useful information for the public, U Kin Tong said.
</P>
<P>
His views were echoed by Lok Po, deputy editor-in-chief of the
Macao Daily News, who said that he believed that the freedom of
speech will continue in post-return Macao and the government will
continue to increase transparency in administration and support
the media.
</P>
<P>
As a newspaper with the biggest circulation in Macao, Macao
Daily News will continue to carry three commentaries every day as
a means to supervise the government. "We will continue to serve as
a bridge between the people and government by publishing the voice
of the commonplace people," Lok Po said.
</P>
<P>
To maintain its independence, Macao Daily News won't receive
government subsidies, according to Lok Po.
</P>
<P>
Victor Chan, a deputy head of the news department in Macao TV
Station, said people are entitled to have different thoughts in an
open society like Macao and the purpose of his television station
is to express these thoughts of the people.
</P>
<P>
This tradition will continue in the future with legal support
and the efforts from the press, Victor Chan predicted.
</P>
<P>
Actually, this function of the press will be further
highlighted in post-return Macao, since the residents will place
higher hopes on the SAR government and the SAR government also
needs to learn about the public opinion and expectations for the
sake of the government administration, economic development and
social security, he added.
</P>
<P>
"All the social problems in Macao can't be solved overnight,"
Victor Chan said, adding that "What we hope is to help the
government to map out long-term policies and thereby contribute to
the prosperity and development of Macao." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
