<HEADLINE> Interview: HK, Macao Hand in Hand into New Millennium (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Senior leaders of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) government Thursday
expressed their hope that they will seize every opportunity to
enhance cooperation with the newly-born Macao SAR government into
the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Just four days before China's resumption of sovereignty over
Macao, the Hong Kong SAR leaders said that they would like share
with the new team of Macao officials the success of the China's
first SAR established in Hong Kong in 1997 and their experience in
implementing the great concept of "One Country, Two Systems" over
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the reversion of sovereignty over Macao to China
and look forward to cooperating with the Macao SAR in matters of
mutual concern," Anson Chan, the SAR administrative secretary,
told Xinhua exclusively.
</P>
<P>
Chan believed that the "One Country, Two systems" concept is a
unique concept "with no precedent to guide us".
</P>
<P>
"Its success depends on the commitment of the two parties
involved, that is the sovereign power and the special
administrative region, to abide by the provisions of the Joint
Declaration and the Basic Law," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
Chan stressed that a great deal of work went into fleshing out
the principles laid down in these two documents. Since July 1,
1997, the Hong Kong SAR has enjoyed a high degree of autonomy and
the Hong Kong people are running Hong Kong under the leadership of
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa, she added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chan noted that the Central Government has strictly
complied with the Joint Declaration and the Basic Law and has not
interfered in matters falling within the autonomy of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
"The rule of law continues to be the cornerstone of Hong Kong's
stability and prosperity, our judiciary remains independent, and
Hong Kong's way of life has not changed," Chan explained.
</P>
<P>
All the rights and freedoms including freedom of the press, of
expression and assembly guaranteed in the Joint Declaration and
the Basic Law remain intact, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: HK, Macao Hand in Hand into New Millennium (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking of Hong Kong's economic development over the past two
years, Donald Tsang Yam-kuen, financial secretary of the Hong Kong
SAR, said that the Basic Law provides a solid legal foundation for
Hong Kong's continued economic success.
</P>
<P>
The SAR is given full autonomy in economic and financial
matters, and maintains its own currency. "Indeed we are charged
with the duty under the Basic Law to maintain Hong Kong's status
as an international financial center," he told Xinhua in an
exclusive interview.
</P>
<P>
In the two years since the establishment of the SAR, Hong Kong'
s economy was seriously affected by the Asian financial crisis.
Prices are falling and unemployment rate is over 6 percent, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We experienced a painful but necessary adjustment process
during this period, with companies downsizing and rationalizing
their operations to increase competitiveness and efficiency,"
Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
Tsang stressed that entrepreneurs and the workforce have
demonstrated great resilience and endurance in this difficult
adjustment period. Reforms are implemented in the banking and
financial sectors to increase our competitiveness, he added.
</P>
<P>
"All these are now bearing fruit as the economy is recovering,
with the third quarter GDP growth at 4.5 percent and the growth
forecast for 1999 as a whole revised upward to 1.8 percent," Tsang
said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "our adherence to the principle of fiscal prudence as
enshrined in the Basic Law enables us to build up sizable reserves,
and this makes it possible for the government to finance budget
deficits in the past two years to alleviate the burden on the
public during the financial crisis."
</P>
<P>
With China's imminent accession to the World Trade Organization,
plans to spearhead local development on innovation and technology,
the agreement with Walt Disney Company to build a theme park,
there is a horizon of opportunities ahead of Hong Kong, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
