<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, December 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Syrian and Israeli negotiation teams held
about 80 minutes of talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright attendance at the U.S. official guest house, Blair House,
on Wednesday after an opening ceremony at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The talks then adjourned until Thursday's 11:00 a.m. 1600 GMT
</P>
<P>
No substantive details of the talks were released because of
effective news blackout for the two days of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told a briefing after the
Blair House meeting at 4:30 p.m. (2130 GMT) that Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara
discussed with Albright how to move toward a peace agreement,
which Middle East experts believe could not be reached until the
settlement of the dispute over the Golan Heights, the Syrian
territory snatched by Israel during the 1967 six-day war. (Syria-
Israel-Washington Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The Government of the People's Republic of China and
the Government of the United States of America reached an
agreement on December 16, 1999 on the question of compensation
relating to the U.S. bombing of the Chinese Embassy in the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY).
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu
Bangzao here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the U.S. Government will pay a sum
of 28 million U.S. dollars to the Chinese Government for the
property loss and damage suffered by China as a result of the U.S.
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in FRY last May.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this, the two sides, on July 30, already reached an
agreement on the question of compensation for Chinese casualties
resulting from the U.S. bombing of the Chinese Embassy in FRY. (
China-US-Embassy Bombing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Despite torrential rains, Venezuelans went out to
vote on Wednesday in a referendum on the country's new
constitution promoted by President Hugo Chavez.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 11 million Venezuelans should vote Wednesday on a
proposed constitution that would transform the nation, changing
its name, eliminating the senate and giving President Hugo Chavez
the opportunity to stay in office for up to 13 years. (Venezuela-
New Constitution) 
</P>
