<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder, Clinton Agree on Nazi Slave Labor Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder said Wednesday that he and U.S. President Bill Clinton
had agreed on a fund of 10 billion marks (4.7 billion U.S. dollars)
to compensate millions of slave laborers during Germany's Nazi era,
ending year-long negotiations on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said he and Clinton had agreed both on the sum and
measures to protect German firms against new legal demands for
further compensations on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The chief U.S. negotiator, Deputy Secretary of Treasury Stuart
Eizenstat, flew to Berlin on Wednesday evening in an effort to
hammer out with his German counterpart Otto Graf Lambsdorff the
details of a final German-U.S. solution that will be signed on
Friday at the G-8 Foreign Ministers' meeting here.
</P>
<P>
Lambsdorff told Berlin Info Radio that the German side would
offer 5,000 to 6,000 marks (2,630 to 3,150 dollars) as
compensation for each forced laborer and about 15,000 marks (7,840
dollars) for each slave laborer in concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
Neither Schroeder nor Lambsdorff spelled out how much the
German government would contribute to the fund.
</P>
<P>
So far, Berlin had agreed to pay three billion marks (1.57
billion dollars) and the German businesses had offered five
billion marks (2.63 billion dollars). But Finance Minister Hans
Eichel said that the German federal government had no more money
to spare and might sell part of its holdings.
</P>
<P>
"Under this condition, the federal government must sell
something from its ownership," Eichel told the ZDF television
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said he hoped Germany's 16 state governments would
participate in the fund initiative and he planned to call a
session with the state premiers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Wolfgang Gibowski, spokesman for the German businesses of the
fund initiative, told Deutsche Presse Agentur (DPA) news agency
that some 26 German firms, including such big names as Daimler-
Chrysler, BMW, Siemens, Hoechst and BASF, had committed themselves
to participating in the fund.
</P>
<P>
"There must be more member companies, if people expect the
German businesses to offer more than five billion marks," said
Gibowski, adding that at least 65 German companies would finally
take part in the fund.
</P>
<P>
The Nazi German dictatorship had forced over 8 million
Europeans to supplement its depleting labor force during World War
II. Hundreds of thousands of the forced laborers died of
maltreatment, and the survivors have been demanding compensation
for the terrible abuses they had suffered.
</P>
<P>
The negotiating process, starting from 1998 when lawyers suited
German firms in U.S. courts, has been focused on how to compensate
the victims, most of whom are in their 70s or 80s and are dying
off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
