<HEADLINE> China Attacks Illegal Medicine Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China has shut down
dozens of illicit pharmaceutical markets and revoked the licenses
of thousands of medicine producers and traders this year, a
senior official from the Supervision Department said.
</P>
<P>
 Vice-Minister of Supervision Li Zhilun said that 83 medicine
markets had been shut down in 15 provinces and regions,and another
seven have been warned to redress their irregular practices.
</P>
<P>
Authorities also seized fake or expired medicines worth 300
million yuan (about 36 million U.S. dollars) and dealt with many
cases, he said.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown has come at a time when illegal medicine
producers and traders are appearing in several places, causing
losses to consumers and posing threats to the health of patients.
</P>
<P>
Beginning this year, the central government ordered various
industrial and commercial administrations to exercise strict
checks on medicine manufacturers and salesmen. The State
Development Planning Commission lowered the prices of costly
medicines, including 24 kinds of domestic and 114 imported
medicines, by 10 and five percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is also a member of the Standing Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Commission for Discipline
Inspection, said that those who take kickbacks from the sales of
medicine and fake medicine producers will face stern disciplinary
or legal punishment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
