<HEADLINE> Restoration of Ancient City Wall in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Restoration of the wall
of the 300-year old Chengde Imperial Summer Resort in north China'
s Hebei Province is now finished and the structure recently
reopened to the public.
</P>
<P>
The resort was built during the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911). As
the world's largest imperial garden, it was named on the World
Heritage List by the United Nations Educational Scientific and
Cultural Organization (UNESCO) in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The ten-kilometer wall, which is an important part of the
resort as well as the ancient palaces and buildings in the area,
has long been blocked from view by stretches of illegal
residential buildings and construction projects, according to a
local cultural official.
</P>
<P>
The restoration project was started in October by removing the
buildings near the wall, involving an area of 20,000 square meters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
