<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Expect Continued U.S. Economic Growth in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economic growth
that began nearly nine years ago will continue in 2000, though at
a slower pace than in the past several years, a report said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report from the Bond Market Association said that its
Economic Advisory Committee, which is composed of noted economists
from securities firms and banks, also expects additional
tightening by the Federal Reserve during 2000, probably in March,
resulting in somewhat higher interest rates. The unemployment
rate is expected to hold at or below 1999 level through 2000, but
without any rise in inflation.
</P>
<P>
In the foreign exchange markets, the committee expects the euro
to recover from its recent weakness, climbing to 1.14 U.S. dollars
by the end of 2000. The yen is predicted to give back some of its
recent gains and end the year at 107 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. gross domestic product (GDP), according to the
committee, will average a 3.9 percent growth rate in 1999. GDP
growth for 2000 is expected to decline to 3 percent, attributable,
in part, to Y2K factors in the first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
Consumer Price Index inflation in 1999 is forecast at 2.6
percent. For 2000, it is expected to inch down to 2.4 percent,
and the unemployment rate is anticipated to decline slightly from
4.2 percent in 1999 to 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates are expected to close out 2000 above the current
level, with the median forecast at 6.7 percent for the 30-year
Treasury bond.
</P>
<P>
Committee members anticipated the budget surplus will swell to
nearly 140 billion dollars by the end of 2000, up from 123 billion
dollars this year and 69 billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In general, the report said, the committee members believe the
Fed has done a good job in conducting monetary in 1999. But some
group members said the Fed should have acted sooner to slow the
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
