<HEADLINE> NW China Province Clamps Down on Economic Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Shaanxi Province in northwest
China has cracked down on more than 20,000 economic crimes in
recent years, retrieving a loss of some 1.5 billion yuan (180
million U.S. dollars), according to local police sources.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi provincial police departments have gone to great
lengths to resolve some high-profile crimes, including a few
nationwide swindling cases, which may jeopardize the public
interest and threaten social security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they also worked together to close seven cases of
smuggling of cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
So far, some 39,700 precious cultural relics, dating from the
Western Zhou Dynasty (1100 B.C.-771 B.C) to the Tang Dynasty (618-
907), have been recovered and over 7,000 suspects, including 218
people from overseas, were sued to be involved in the smuggling
cases.
</P>
<P>
China's police units have been going all out in the fight
against crime, but problems still remain, as some criminal
suspects are still at large.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to beef up a nationwide drive to deal
severely with criminals, Minister of Public Security Jia Chunwang
said recently, adding that public security departments at all
levels will focus on reinforcing grassroots units and setting up a
contract system for police units in the next couple of years.
</P>
</TEXT>
