<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronicle of the Macao Question (1987-1999)(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
June, 23, 1987, the Standing Committee of the Sixth National
People's Congress (NPC) approved the Sino-Portuguese Joint
Declaration on the Question of Macao.
</P>
<P>
September 21, 1987, Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch was set up,
with Zhou Ding serving as director.
</P>
<P>
December 11, 1987, the Portuguese congress approved the Sino-
Portuguese Joint Declaration.
</P>
<P>
January 15, 1988, Chinese and Portuguese governments exchanged
their instruments of ratification for the joint declaration in
Beijing and thus Macao entered the period of transition.
</P>
<P>
March 22, 1988, the joint declaration was registered and
publicized at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
September 5, 1988, the Third Session of the Seventh NPC
Standing Committee approved the roll of the Drafting Committee for
the Basic Law of the Macao Special Administrative Region (MSAR) of
the People's Republic of China (PRC).
</P>
<P>
October 25, 1988, the Drafting Committee for the Basic Law of
the MSAR held its first plenary session in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
February 15, 1989, the Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group
began its formal operation in Macao.
</P>
<P>
April 9, 1989, the roll of the 90-member Consulting Committee
for the Basic Law of the MSAR was made public.
</P>
<P>
April 10, 1991, the Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group signed
an agreement confirming the official status of the Chinese
Language in Macao.
</P>
<P>
December 11, 1991, the Macao Visa Office of the People's
Republic of China was set up.
</P>
<P>
December 12, 1991, the cabinet of Portugal issued a decree
allowing the Chinese language to enjoy the same official status
and legal power as the Portuguese language in Macao.
</P>
<P>
January 13-15, 1993, the Drafting Committee for the Basic Law
of the MSAR, at its ninth plenary session, adopted a draft Basic
Law of the MSAR and draft patterns of MSAR's regional flag and
emblem.
</P>
<P>
March 31, 1993, the First Session of the Eighth NPC Standing
Committee examined and approved the draft Basic Law of the MSAR.
The session also passed a resolution on the establishment of the
MSAR and a resolution on methods for the formation of the first
government, legislative council and judicial organs of the MSAR.
It also approved the regional flag and emblem of the MSAR.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finnish, Russian Prime Ministers Discuss Chechnya Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Discussing the situation in Chechnya with Putin over telephone,
Lipponen, on behalf of EU, stressed the need to hammer out a
political solution to end the war, hoping that Russia would seize
the opportunity offered by the Organization of Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to open dialogue with the rebels in
order to solve the crisis in the region. Meanwhile he also
restated that the EU condemns terrorism in all forms and respects
the integrity of Russian territory.
</P>
<P>
During the discussion, the Finnish prime minister emphasized
that both the EU and Finland aim at developing cooperation with
Russia on a long-term basis and supporting the democratic
development and stability in Russia, without intending to isolate
Russia from the sphere of European cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Prime Minister explained the actions taken by the
Russian government and its efforts to find a political solution to
the crisis in Chechnya. At the same time, he said Russia is ready
to cooperate in providing aids for the refugees.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Putin also said that Russia will provide
transport for OSCE President, Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut
Vollebaek, to Chechnya as soon as weather conditions permit.
</P>
<P>
The EU is now deeply concerned about the humanitarian
situation and problems encountered by the refugees in the area.
The European Council has not decided to impose sanctions on Russia
immediately although the decisions taken by the Helsinki European
Council will lead to a review of cooperation between the EU and
Russia if no political solution is found for the situation in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Finland currently holds the rotating EU presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
