<HEADLINE> Macao's Return Becomes Focus of Chinese Websites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Macao and the return of Macao to
China have become a central theme of many Chinese-language
websites.
</P>
<P>
The word "Macao" can lead an Internet buff to a big number of
Chinese-language websites as the day of Macao's return to China,
December 20, is close at hand.
</P>
<P>
With the word "Macao," the search engine of Yahoo! can locate
184 Chinese-language websites that are related to Macao. Sixteen
of them are devoted exclusively to the region's return to China.
</P>
<P>
Names of the websites include "Macao 1999," "Into Macao" and "
Come Back, Macao." The websites are either of an official or a
private type. And contents are either in simplified Chinese used
in the Chinese mainland or in unsimplified Chinese prevalent
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
From these websites, readers from around the world can not only
follow events in the runup to the December 20 handover but also
browse for local information. Electronic maps of Macao are among
downloadable items on many sites.
</P>
<P>
On a site operated by a Guangdong-based company is a forum that
encourages readers to contribute their diaries, thoughts and
photos during the handover period. The site has so far recorded
more than 40,000 hits.
</P>
<P>
Another site run by the Qingdao municipal committee of the
Chinese Communist Youth League, a contest with Macao's return to
China as the theme is going on. On the message board of the site
writes a 12-year girl from Hong Kong: "I like Macao. The
motherland will become more beautiful after Macao's return."
</P>
<P>
A 19-year-old girl, Zhang Yuhong, writes: "I look forward to
Macao's return."
</P>
<P>
A primary school teacher in Shanghai has submitted an open
letter on the site, saying that each and every student of her
school has written a letter to students in Macao and hopes that
their letters will reach their destinations.
</P>
<P>
Most Internet activities relating to Macao's return have come
from college students.
</P>
<P>
As Macao is at the threshold of a new era, the Internet is seen
as a witness of its historic moment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
