<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao's Manpower Exceeds 200,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- With the increasing influx of
immigrants, Macao's labor force has exceeded 200,000, according to
a local official.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Macao's population reached 436,000 by 1998,
70 percent more than that in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The increasing population has boosted domestic demands and
provided a large number of cheap labor to local economy, the
processing and service industries in particular.
</P>
<P>
However, the high population density and relatively developed
economy, with yearly gross domestic output (GDP) reporting at
around 60 billion patacas, also make Macao face a labor shortage.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, Macao began to import labor, averaging more than 9,000
a year. To date, overseas labor has made up 15 percent of the
employees in Macao. Of the imported labor, about 70 percent are
from China's inland areas while the rest from Southeast Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Macao's employment rate stands at 97.3 percent. Of the employed,
37.5 percent are working in service trade and 20.6 percent in
manufacturing sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accord Signed on Creating Kosovo's Interim Administration Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the U.N. special
mission in Kosovo Bernard Kouchner and three ethnic Albanian
leaders signed an agreement Wednesday on creating an interim
administration body to run the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
In Kosovo's capital Pristina, Kouchner signed the document
along with former leader of the Kosovo Liberation Army Hassim
Thacci, President of the Kosovo Democratic League Ibrahim Rugova
and Chief of the United Democratic Movement Redzep Djosja.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, an eight-member interim administration
commission will be established and govern the province until
elections are held in the province. Half of its members will come
from the U.N. mission and the other half from Kosovo delegates --
the above three Albanian leaders and one from the Serb minority.
</P>
<P>
Kouchner will head the commission and have a right to veto
decisions made by it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
