<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria, Israel Hold First-Day Session of Washington Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 ( Xinhua ) -- The Syrian and Israeli
negotiation teams held about 80 minutes of talks with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright attendance at the U.S.
official guest house, Blair House, on Wednesday after an opening
ceremony at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The talks then adjourned until Thursday's 11:00 a.m. 1600 GMT
</P>
<P>
No substantive details of the talks were released because of
effective news blackout for the two days of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told a briefing after the
Blair House meeting at 4:30 p.m. (2130 GMT) that Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara
discussed with Albright how to move toward a peace agreement,
which Middle East experts believe could not be reached until the
settlement of the dispute over the Golan Heights, the Syrian
territory snatched by Israel during the 1967 six-day war.
</P>
<P>
"It's not surprising there are real differences at this point,
but both parties displayed a serious intent and the president
remains firm in his commitment to help them in this effort,"
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton met with Barak and Shara first together
after the ceremony then separately.
</P>
<P>
"They're going pretty well, but it's hard going and we've got
some work to do," Clinton told reporters after his meeting with
the two team leaders.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said Clinton "laid out how he thinks we should move
forward and where we should get to at the end of the two days" and
both sides had agreed to that.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli official said Israeli and Syrian negotiators will
reconvene their meeting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There were no public handshakes between Barak and Shara, which
disappointed news photographers who hoped there would have been a
routine gesture of diplomatic symbolism by handshaking.
</P>
<P>
Israeli political sources said that the Syrian team had asked
no show of public handshakes at the outset of the talks. U.S.
officials said it would be inappropriate ahead of any peace deal
as Israel and Syria are still officially in a state of war.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said that despite the lack of handshakes, the talks
were an historic step.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister of Israel and the foreign minister of Syria
have never sat down to talk about anything, much less peace
between the two countries ... I think the statements today
recognized long-standing differences, but there was also a spirit
of reconciliation that I don't think anyone's heard before," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
