<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Business Inventories Rise 0.2 Percent in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Commerce
Department said Wednesday that the country's stockpiles of goods
on shelves and backlots increased by 0.2 percent in October,
pushing total business inventories to 1.26 trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Though marking the slowest growth in business inventories since
April, October's gain was the ninth straight monthly increase this
year. In September, total business inventories rose by 0.4
percent, the fastest pace in six months.
</P>
<P>
Sales jumped by a solid 0.5 percent in October, the largest
increase since August, while in September it fell by 0.2 percent,
the first decline since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The rise in October's sales brought the inventory-to-sales
ratio to 1.33, meaning it would take 1.33 months to exhaust
inventories at the October sales pace.
</P>
<P>
Inventories rose by 0.3 percent at wholesalers and at factories
in October, but were flat at retailers. The numbers indicate that
businesses are not hoarding goods in anticipation of the Y2K
computer changeover.
</P>
<P>
Sales were the strongest in October at wholesalers, rising 0.7
percent. They grew by 0.4 percent at factories and 0.3 percent at
retailers.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Purchasing Management said Tuesday
it expects the industrial sector to continue strong surge and to
bring in higher revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
