<HEADLINE> Man United Director Rules Out more Big Paydays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Martin Edwards said Manchester
United players would be disappointed if they think Roy Keane's new
blockbusting contract will mean big pay rises for them.
</P>
<P>
United smashed their infamous wage ceiling to make Keane the
best paid player in Britain in a deal worth a reported 50,000
pounds per week.
</P>
<P>
Edwards claimed the mega deal was in the commercial interests
of the Treble winners, but he insisted it would not open the
floodgates for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
Virtually all of United's big stars like David Beckham, Ryan
Giggs and Paul Scholes are tied up under long-term agreements.
</P>
<P>
Edwards is not about to renegotiate all those contracts and
instead each case will be judged on its merits when the time comes.
</P>
<P>
"Each player who comes in, we will have to judge each case on
its merits," said the United chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
"If he's a vital player for Manchester United, the board will
know how far it needs to go, but I don't think this changes a lot.
</P>
<P>
"If players think, or agents think, that this is going to open
the floodgates for everyone else, I don't think it will because we
will judge each case on its merits.
</P>
<P>
"It may be in some cases that certain players are going to be
disappointed with future negotiations, but we've got to run
Manchester United as a business and we will continue to do so," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
