<HEADLINE> Newcastle United Face Court Action in Ticket Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- English premier league soccer
club Newcastle United are facing High Court proceedings over their
decision to move season-ticket holders to accommodate corporate
clients at St James' Park.
</P>
<P>
Solicitors have issued proceedings against the club at the High
Court in Leeds on behalf of bondholder Jane Duffy, leader of the
Save Our Seats campaign which was mounted when the club announced
plans to move up to 4,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
Duffy is seeking an injunction preventing the club from
depriving her of her current seat and a ruling that the 500 pounds
bond she purchased in 1994 entitles her to a specific seat.
</P>
<P>
Alternatively, she wants the club to accept that she could only
be moved to a seat of equal quality.
</P>
<P>
The action also demands damages for breach of contract and
misrepresentation and costs. 
</P>
