<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Higher On Windows 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 65.15 at 11,225.32.
The blue chip index fell 32.42 points Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 10.15 at 1,413.32 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 50.29 at 3,621.95.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rallied as Microsoft said its Windows 2000 code has been
delivered to software manufacturing plants and Windows 2000-based
products will be put on the market on February 17 next year.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft's shares rose, pushing the market higher. The
software giant has recently bounced back from a drop that began
last month when a federal judge said the company had abused its
monopoly in the software business.
</P>
<P>
But most Internet stocks fell. Among them were Yahoo!, Amazon.
com, eBay and Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 0.14 at 631.93 and the Russell 2000 index
of smaller companies fell 1.43 at 461.32. But the American Stock
Exchange index rose 11.16 at 838.94.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,662 down, 1,430 up and 484
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.022 billion shares from 1.017
billion in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
