<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Appoints Two Junior Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Two junior ministers were
appointed to Northern Ireland's new power-sharing executive in
Belfast on Wednesday following a heated debate, the BBC reported.
</P>
<P>
The selection of Ulster Unionist Dermot Nesbitt and Denis
Haughey from the Social Democratic and Labor Party (SDLP) followed
a day of heated exchanges in the assembly over whether the
appointments should go ahead.
</P>
<P>
The new posts were agreed upon by the assembly following calls
by both first Minister David Trimble and first deputy Miniter
Seamus Mallon.
</P>
<P>
However, there were heated exchanges regarding how these posts
would be filled.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Unionist Party Social Development Minister Nigel
Dodds said it was a case of "jobs for the boys" during Tuesday
evening's debate.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein assemblyman Mitchel McLaughlin expressed reservations
because both of the new junior ministers would have no specific
brief and would serve as ministers without portfolio.
</P>
<P>
The assembly narrowly voted to back the decision by the first
minister and deputy first minister to appoint the two junior
ministers at Stormont, Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The vote was 49 in favor and 38 against despite opposition from
all other parties in the assembly except the Ulster Unionists and
SDLP.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sinn Fein, the Political wing of the Irish
Republican Army, called on public bodies to stop flying the Union
flag. 
</P>
