<HEADLINE> Britain Opens First Hospital Cinema </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua)-- Britain has opened its first
hospital cinema to offer bed-ridden patients the chance to enjoy
the silver screen, the Daily Telegraph reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The cinema at St Thomas's Hospital, London, has places for a
seated audience of 98 plus 10 wheelchair spaces and room for six
beds.
</P>
<P>
It will show films on general release at mainstream cinemas
during matinee performances for children and evening shows for
adult patients.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's opening ceremony, Kate Winslet, star of the
blockbuster movie Titanic and patron of Medicinema, the charity
responsible for the hospital cinema, said, "I think it's a great
idea to enable patients to forget about their worries, aches and
pains by losing themselves in the magic of the silver screen."
</P>
<P>
Minister for film Janet Anderson said she applauded the
partnership between the health sector and the film industry.
</P>
<P>
The cinema is the result of three years' planning and has been
built in a converted part of King's College medical school at St
Thomas's and St Guy's Hospital Trust.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the building will operate as a lecture theater
for staff at the hospitals, converting to a cinema at weekends.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the charity said, "We don't want patients to
feel isolated from the outside world. The cinema will show up to
date films and maybe some classics too."
</P>
<P>
Plans to build a further 20 hospital cinemas around the country
are under discussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
