<HEADLINE> Putin: National Interests Dictate Ties With CIS Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Vladimir Putin
said here Wednesday that Russia's national interests will be the "
only main priority" in its relations with other members of the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS).
</P>
<P>
Putin told a meeting of the Russian Security Council, a top
advisory body, that ties with CIS countries should occupy an
absolutely dominant position in its foreign affairs as there are
hundreds of thousands of ethnic Russians and Russian-speaking
people living in those countries.
</P>
<P>
The CIS groups 12 of the 15 former Soviet republics. The three
Baltic countries -- Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania -- stayed out of
the organization, which was set up following the disintegration of
the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Putin said Moscow has no plan to declare any of the CIS states
a "zone of its strategic interests," the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Instead, "it will be right if we propose strategic partnership
to any of the Commonwealth countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's ties with other CIS countries are based on the fact
that Russia, as the inheritor of the Soviet Union, commands a
natural monopolistic position in energy, transport and
communications, Putin said.
</P>
<P>
He called for the restoration of the original economic ties,
though not necessarily to the original levels.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said international events over the past
several months have indicated that former Soviet republics are "
the natural allies of Russia."
</P>
<P>
He said the goals and tasks for Russia's policies toward the
CIS countries remain unchanged, but the methods and means in
achieving those goals should be improved.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has decided to set up an inter-
departmental group that specializes in the study of Russian
policies toward those countries, Putin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
