<HEADLINE> UK Woman to Challenge Test-tube Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- A British woman who had her
eggs frozen while she underwent cancer treatment has found she is
not legally allowed to try for a baby, the BBC reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Now a High Court challenge has been launched by a leading
London fertility clinic in an attempt to change the regulations.
</P>
<P>
Carolyn Neill, 34, from Belfast, was told by doctors that
radiotherapy was almost certain to render her infertile, but as
she did not have a partner, she opted to store some unfertilized
eggs for future use.
</P>
<P>
Now she has been declared free from cancer, she wants to start
a family.
</P>
<P>
However, while the government watchdog which regulates
fertility treatment in the UK allows women to have their eggs
frozen, it does not allow doctors to subsequently fertilize them -
or even thaw them.
</P>
<P>
And Carolyn even needs official permission to take her eggs
abroad to a country which allows the procedure.
</P>
<P>
The Human Fertilization and Embryology Authority says it is not
yet convinced that the procedure would result in healthy babies,
even though it has been carried out more than 30 times in
countries such as Italy and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Carolyn Neill's eggs are currently stored at the Assisted
Reproduction and Gynaecology Center in London, whose director, Dr
Mohammed Taranissi, is battling for the procedure to be approved.
</P>
<P>
The fertilization authority is due to review the issue of
frozen eggs in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0374 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: U.S. Attaches Importance to Energy Development in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUCSON, the Unites States, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. and
African energy ministers concluded their three-day conference here
Wednesday afternoon with the U.S. government vowing to forge a
strengthened energy partnership between America and Africa.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, the first of its kind in gathering the U.
S. and African energy ministers nearly on a continent-wide basis,
Bill Richardson, the U.S. secretary of energy, and Susan Rice,
assistant secretary of state for African affairs, both voiced the
U.S. strong commitment to further U.S.-African energy cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The event, with the theme of "A Partnership for the 21st
Century," also follows up on President Bill Clinton's historic
visit to Africa last year.
</P>
<P>
"This conference is a cornerstone of my African Energy
Initiative to foster energy cooperation and sustainable
development in Africa into the next century and beyond,"
Richardson said Tuesday at the conference's plenary session.
</P>
<P>
Energy development in Africa is crucial to the United States,
whose energy appetite has been skyrocketing over the past five
decades. The reasons are very evident.
</P>
<P>
First, the United States, the only economic and political
superpower in today's world, is anxious to maintain its energy
security as it is increasingly depending on African energy,
massively described as "blood for economic advancement." Following
the U.S. bid for the Caspian Sea oil, the United States is turning
its eyes on Africa for its future steady source of energy,
</P>
<P>
In 1988, Africa exported some 1.4 million barrels of oil a day
to the United States, about 17 percent of total U.S. oil imports,
against the backdrop of 23 percent imported by the U.S. from the
oil-rich Gulf region. At present, Africa is the eighth-largest
exporter of petroleum to the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Americans are depending increasingly on Africa, one of the
world's untapped energy markets, to fuel cars, to heat living
rooms and to power industry, " Rice said Tuesday at the plenary
session.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the Clinton Administration wants to work very closely
with Africa to increase American investment on the continent,
especially in the electricity grid, in energy renewable projects,
and in sustainable energy development.
</P>
<P>
The United States is seeking more business opportunities in
African energy development as energy demand by African industries
is projected to grow by 4 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
In fact, both energy consumption and production in Africa have
been on the rise. "Commercial energy consumption is growing
throughout Africa," the U.S. Department of Energy said in its
statistical information. "Energy demand growth in Africa averaged
2.7 percent annually from 1980 through 1970, and a slightly faster
3.1 percent annual average from 1990 and 1997."
</P>
<P>
As Rice put it Tuesday, "Americans are working hard to be both
investors and consumers of African energy." That mirrors
significant U.S. commercial interest in Africa, especially in the
energy sector.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the U.S. Department of Energy is working in Ghana on
solar energy projects, in South Africa on energy efficiency, and
in Uganda to develop geothermal resources. "We have established
successful partnerships with Egypt and Morocco, and we are making
progress in our partnerships with Nigeria and Senegal," Richardson
has said.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, Washington hopes to develop more common strategies
with Africa on climate change policies, on issues relating to the
reduction of greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
Africa now has relatively low overall carbon emissions, but
these are expected to soar in the next century, according to
Richardson.
</P>
<P>
African carbon emissions from fossil fuel consumption,
excluding natural gas flaring, are growing rapidly, although from
a very small base. "Carbon emissions in Africa roughly tripled,
from 72 million metric tons (Mmt) in 1970 to 202 Mmt in 1997, and
are projected to reach 325 Mmt in 2020," said the figures from the
U.S. Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
"Africa's share of world carbon emissions has increased
slightly from 2 percent in 1970 to around 2 percent in 1997, and
is expected to remain about constant through 2020," according to
the statistics.
</P>
<P>
However, what Africans need is not words, but actions. In
Africa, where some country was counting ballots under dim candle
light and many Africans have never seen bulbs, fair play in the
world markets and apolitical investments are the two challenges
facing the continent, which is being growingly marginalized in the
current globalization process.
</P>
<P>
The United States should not only focus its attention on Africa
's energy sector, but also take effective actions against the
heavy debt burden in many African countries and HIV/AIDS disease,
which created massive orphanage in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Just like what an African energy minister said here during the
conference, "it seems that the U.S. is getting more serious about
Africa, but we Africans do need genuine actions, rather than lip
service." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991216.0375 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., African Energy Ministers Issue Tucson Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUCSON, the United States, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. and
African energy ministers Wednesday afternoon issued the Tucson
Communique here, saying that they vowed to strengthen energy
cooperation among and between the United States and African
countries.
</P>
<P>
The communique came at the end of the three-day U.S.-African
Energy Ministers Conference, which, beginning here Monday, was the
first international event that has gathered the U.S. energy
minister, Bill Richardson, and some 50 of his African counterparts
in this sun-shining city.
</P>
<P>
"In this meeting, the Ministers focused on policies and
practices that promote economic development, address environmental
concerns, encourage private investment, enhance regional
integration, and increase access to energy for Africa's people,"
the communique said.
</P>
<P>
"Such successful policies and practices will lead to the
creation of sustainable energy infrastructure for Africa in the
21st century and will advance Africa's economic and social
development," it said.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministers recognized the progress that has been achieved,
individually and collectively through bilateral, regional,
multilateral and international efforts, towards developing Africa'
s energy sector in a way that meets their mutual political,
economic, social and environmental goals," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, the ministers accepted the invitation
of the government of Morocco to host a conference on sustainable
energy technology next year. Meanwhile, they accepted the
invitation of the government of South Africa to host a ministers
meeting next year and the invitation of the government of Algeria
to host a preparatory experts meeting next year and assess their
progress in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministers endorsed a Joint Statement on Sustainable
Energy Development and Cooperation in Support of the Environment,
confirming their agreement to implement sustainable energy
policies and promote clean energy options," the communique said.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministers, aware that private investment and partnership
are crucial to meeting Africa's growing energy needs in the 21st
century, issued a Joint Statement on Investment Principles for the
Energy Sector, demonstrating their agreement to create or sustain
the conditions that encourage investment in the energy sector,"
the communique added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
